<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Unconcerned by Russia Bomber Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that it was unconcerned by the incident in which two
Russian strategic bombers was reportedly intercepted by U.S.
fighter jets near Iceland.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that the incident was
not "a militarily significant event."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. routinely protects the airspace of Iceland and I
don't think there's anyone who believed that these two propeller
bombers posed a significant military threat," he said.
</P>
<P>
Two Russian strategic bombers flew with striking distance of
the U.S. last week as part of Moscow's largest military exerciseds
since the end of the Cold War, The Washington Post reported in its
Thursday's edition.
</P>
<P>
The TU-95 Bear bombers were intercepted by four U.S. F-15
fighters and a P-3 patrol plane near Iceland early Friday morning
and escorted in a clockwise flight around the island, the
newspaper quoted U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
The incident astounded U.S. officials and underlined recent
Western concerns about the military leadership in Moscow, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley said that
the bombers were international airspace as part of a military
exercise announced in advance by the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
"Russia routinely holds military exercises and we are not
particularly troubled by this. I don't think that there's any
need to over-dramatize this," Crowley added.
</P>
<P>
Moscow also dowplayed the incident by denying any wrongdoing.
"Our planes did not violate any laws in that area," a Russian Air
Force spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
