<HEADLINE> Angolan Army Recovers Strategic Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Angolan army Thursday recovered
Mbazi, a strategic position outside the central highland city
Huambo, putting an end to the constant shelling of the city by the
opposition National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA).
</P>
<P>
According to a military source who preferred not to reveal his
name, the UNITA forces often launch bombardment and even attacks
at the city and its suburbs from Mbazi, a highland 40 kilometers
to the north of Huambo, with long-range cannons.
</P>
<P>
The source did not disclose losses of the two sides during the
fighting, but he said the government army has used cannons to
support the ground attacks.
</P>
<P>
Mbazi fell in January this year. The source said its recover
undoubtedly dealt "a heavy blow" to the UNITA forces besieging the
Huambo city.
</P>
<P>
Huambo city has so far witnessed the most fierce fighting in
the war- ravaged southern African country. UNITA forces renewed
its shelling on Huambo city since June 18 and attacked Caala city
40 kilometers away, making the situation more tense in the region.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
