<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A monthly report of the Egyptian Ministry of Economy
has disclosed that Egypt's actual reserves of natural gas amount
to about 1 trillion cubic meters, enough for the coming twenty
years.
</P>
<P>
The report, printed Thursday by Egyptian daily "Alam Al Yom,"
says that Egypt's annual gas production, which now stands at 43.2
million cubic meters, is expected to double by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- The United States has agreed to extend a loan of
651,000 U.S. dollars in the form of technical assistance to
Algeria to improve the performance of projects undertaken in the
field of energy in the country.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The gross domestic product (GDP) of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) dropped by 5.8 percent in 1998, with the share
of the oil sector sinking to 21.7 percent, according to the annual
report of the UAE Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The report, released on Wednesday, said the GDP dropped to
170 billion dirhams (about 46.5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998 due
to the decline in oil revenue.
</P>
<P>
However, non-oil sector performance improved in 1998 thanks to
the government's effort to diversify sources of national income
and to stimulate the performance of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- A memorandum of understanding was signed here Thursday
between Japan and Yemen, according to which Japan will grant 3
million dollars' assistance to Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The grant is aimed at easing Yemen's foreign debt in line with
a decision by the United Nations on relieving the foreign debts of
impoverished countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
