<HEADLINE> WHO to Do More for the Poor's Health: Brundtland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Poverty is an underlying
cause of ill health and under-development and the World Health
Organization (WHO) will mobilize increasing efforts to meet the
goals set by the Cairo Conference 5 years ago.
</P>
<P>
WHO Secretary-General Gro Harlem Brundtland made the remarks at
the on-going special session of the U.N. General Assembly in New
York on Thursday. The meeting is a follow-up to the International
Conference on Population and Development in Cairo in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Pregnancy-related complications, sexually transmitted diseases
and HIV/AIDS account for over one third of all healthy years of
life lost among women of reproductive age in poor countries, but
they can be prevented or managed at low cost, she said.
</P>
<P>
"WHO will work with countries and development partners to
identify and implement key interventions to reduce this
unnecessary burden," she said.
</P>
<P>
She deemed making young people informed about reproductive
health essential for the world to reduce sexually transmitted
diseases, avoid early or unwanted pregnancies and control
population growth.
</P>
<P>
According to Brundtland, there are 333 million new cases of
curable sexually transmitted diseases every year and one in 20
adolescents contracts an STD.
</P>
<P>
Another 5.2 million people are infected by the HIV virus each
year, over half of them young people less than 24 years old.
</P>
<P>
She believed that giving young people information "does not
encourage promiscuity, rather it fosters mutual respect and shared
responsibility". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
