<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief to Visit Europe, Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is scheduled to leave Sunday on a trip to Europe and Africa,
a U.N. spokesman announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Annan will first stop in Geneva where he will open annual
meeting of the U.N. Economic and Social Council and attend a joint
meeting of the U.N. Conference on Trade and Development and the
International Chamber of Commerce, Fred Eckhard, the U.N.
spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, he will begin a five-nation tour of West Africa,
which will take him to Senegal, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Guinea and
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"His trip to West Africa will be primarily to countries where
the U.N. has been heavily involved in peace efforts and then
ending in Nigeria where the secretary-general gave support to the
transition to democracy and the return to civilian rule," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Annan wants to encourage Nigeria's newly elected president,
Olusegun Obasanjo, to continue the process of democratization, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general will also attend the opening of the
Organization of African Unity summit in Algeria on July 11,
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
From July 15-17, he will visit Slovakia and then the Czech
Republic. He will conclude his visit in Vienna where he will open
the third U.N. conference on peaceful uses of outer space on July
19, the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
