<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Has Its Most Deadly Cable Car Accident in 40 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- France had on Thursday its most
deadly cable car accident in 40 years, with 20 people killed in
the fall of a cable car from 80 meters high in the Alps mountain
region.
</P>
<P>
The cable car, which was sending technicians and workers to an
astronomy observatory on a plateau 2,550 meters high, suddenly
disconnected with the cable at 7:30, leaving all its passengers
dead.
</P>
<P>
The accident, which took place near a village called
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy in the Haute-Alpes region in eastern
France, was the most deadly of its kind in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
French officials do not rule out any possibility in the causes
of the fall, including a problem in the pulling strength of the
cable, the wind, and a sudden breakdown of a brake.
</P>
<P>
Most of the dead were employees of the astronomy observatory
who lived in Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy. They commuted to the
observatory everyday on the cable car.
</P>
<P>
The home village of the dead, which had 545 permanent
residents, stayed in a state of shock and a church there has been
turned into a praying chapel for the dead.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous witness said that when he was waiting for the next
car at the cable station, he heard a big sound and saw the car
lying in ruins on the ground under his foot.
</P>
<P>
French television pictures showed the holder of the car and the
cable lying on the ground among the ruins. It is not possible to
see from the pictures how the car dropped.
</P>
<P>
The cable car line, which was opened in 1981, was completely
repaired last year and received many visitors during that year,
said an official of the French national trade union of cable cars
producers.
</P>
<P>
The cable car service exclusively works for the astronomy
observatory, which is quite well known in Europe for its five
gigantic telescopes of 15 meters in diameter specialized in
receiving cosmic radio emissions.
</P>
<P>
The observatory belongs to the French-German Institute of
Millimetric Radio-Astronomy based in the nearby city of Grenoble.
</P>
<P>
The French judicial authorities are expected to launch an
inquiry into those who could be held responsible for manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
France had about a dozen accidents of cable cars over the past
20 years, but none of them as deadly as this one.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said that the country must
draw consequences from the accident, including a ban of cable car
service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
