<HEADLINE> Islamic Group Calls for Intervention in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- An international Islamic relief group
on Thursday called on Muslim countries to intervene to stop armed
hostilities between India and Pakistan over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between the two nuclear powers "is a dangerous
setback to the peace efforts to achieve nuclear stability," the
International Islamic Council for Religious Calling and Relief
said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, carried by Egypt's Middle East News Agency, the
group blamed the international community for failing to contain
the crisis and urged Muslim nations to raise the conflict in
international forums.
</P>
<P>
The group called on the two countries to end their military
actions and show restraint in the crisis, the worst between the
two countries since they last fought a war in 1971.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan have been engaged in fierce fighting for
seven weeks over the disputed Kashmir with scores of casualties on
both sides.
</P>
<P>
India says that the Islamic fighters entrenched the
Indian-controlled part of Kashmir are Pakistani soldiers who
crossed the 1972 cease-fire line that divides Kashmir between the
two neighbors. New Delhi refuses mediation or talks until the
intruders leave.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has said its troops are engaged only in retaliatory
shelling and have not crossed the cease-fire line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
