<HEADLINE> Clinton, Barak Expect Revisal of Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said
on Thursday that he expected to be hosting Israeli Prime
Minister-elect Ehud Barak soon now that Barak is close to forming
a new government.
</P>
<P>
"We now have a real chance to move the peace process forward in
the Middle East," Clinton said at a joint news conference after
his meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would lay out his own ideas for new accords
between Israel and the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"I do think that the time is ripe, but I think that before I
advance publicly any ideas I should have a chance to meet with the
Prime Minister-elect Mr Barak," He said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said Israel should implement agreements it has
already reached with the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he would meet with Israeli and Arab leaders to try
to revive negotiations on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We shall be working with President (Hefez) Assad, Prime
Minister Barak and Chairman (Yasser) Arafat respectively with a
view to creating the necessary atmosphere for resuming the peace
process without delay," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We remain most willing and determined to do all we can," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders this morning held talks mainly on the peace
process which had been stall over the past six months because of
outgoing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's reluctance to
make a further withdrawal from the West Bank in accordance with
the Wye River accord.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said there was an "opportunity that should not be
missed" as Netanyahu was defeated in the May election by Barak who
had shown his intention to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president took the chance here to criticize
israel's bombing of targets in Lebanon last week, calling the
action a threat to the atmosphere for peace, and he urged the
Israelis to exercise "maximum restraint." 
</P>
</TEXT>
