<HEADLINE> WFP to Give $27-Million for Flood Relief in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World
Food Program (WFP) announced on Thursday it is conducting a 27
million U.S. dollar operation for emergency relief and
rehabilitation in Bangladesh following heavy floods there.
</P>
<P>
The year-long operation, ending in May 2000, will focus on
rebuilding activities in addition to food relief for the poorest
and most vulnerable of those affected.
</P>
<P>
Some 2.9 million Bangladeshis will benefit from the aid in a
"food for-work" scheme under which the rations will be given to
those participating in reclaiming rural roads, community fish
ponds, plantations and flood protection.
</P>
<P>
The south Asian country saw unprecedented floods in 1998 which
directly affected more than 30 million people. Two thirds of them
have been aided by WFP, the world's largest food aid agency based
in Rome.  
</P>
</TEXT>
