<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Criticizes British-Dutch Draft on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry has
criticized a draft resolution concerning Iraq, which Britain and
the Netherlands had submitted to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"This document is an attempt at preserving the "Butler" special
commission under a new sign and to even toughen its methods,"
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said at a briefing
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Although this draft envisions several steps for easing the
humanitarian situation in Iraq, it simultaneously imposes new
limitations. They will make the regime of sanctions eternal and
set a sort of humanitarian protectorate in that country," he said.
</P>
<P>
This draft "does not contain the main thing - changes to the
regime of sanctions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has rejected the British-Dutch draft resolution as "a
virulent attempt to undermine Iraq's legitimate right."
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin said that Russia, jointly with China and France,
drafted a resolution concerning Iraq, which "pursues a different
direction."
</P>
<P>
"Our draft is aimed at a resumption of Baghdad's cooperation
with the United Nations via setting up a new international
mechanism for monitoring Iraq's abandonment of prohibited military
programs with the simultaneous lifting of sanctions," he said.
</P>
<P>
This draft reaffirms a comprehensive ban on military
cooperation with Iraq, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
