<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian President Warns Cabinet Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili Muluzi
said Thursday that he is not ready to work with a cabinet that is
prone to corruption at a time when people's expectations are very
high, the Malawi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The president advised his cabinet to desist from the temptation
of corruption and laziness in Blantyre at a swearing-in ceremony
of the cabinet ministers and deputies he appointed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One by one, the 24 available ministers and deputy ministers
swore to "give any counsel and advice to the president" and
"protect and defend the constitution of the Republic of Malawi."
</P>
<P>
Then, Muluzi, in a brief statement, reminded them that they
have been appointed to the cabinet to serve the people, not to
profiteer.
</P>
<P>
"You must serve the people with dedication so that the people
of Malawi improve their lives," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Democracy should imply that people's living standards go up.
Multi- party democracy alone is not enough," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministers should assist him to transform into
reality the dreams of Malawi's 10 million people who need improved
opportunities in commerce and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The president said that his new administration is more
committed to improving the living standards of the people and he
asserted that only serious and hard working cabinet could help
attain that ideal.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi ousted the joint opposition alliance by over 2.4 million
votes and his major rival in the race Gwanda Chakuamba acquired
barely two million votes in the June 15 elections.
</P>
<P>
Malawi held its first democratic multi-party polls in 1994,
ending the over-30-year rule by former President late Hastings
Kamuzu Banda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
