<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Not Lacking Laws Protecting Women, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Attorney-General Bert
Katurebe said Thursday his country has no shortage of law and
treaties that protect the rights of women and children.
</P>
<P>
The attorney-general made the remarks when opening a two-day
workshop on the rights of women and children here Thursday, the
Uganda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Katurebe said that what needs to be done is to have everyone
sensitized about the existence of the law and the need for its
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has put in place various laws that protect the rights of
women and children but government efforts in implementation have
been hampered by lack of resources, the illiteracy of the
population on their rights and the slow eradication of backward
customs, he added.
</P>
<P>
Lack of knowledge by local authorities on their duties toward
children, marginalization of girl children and lack of adequate
trained staff on treaty reporting obligation are also blamed for
hampering the implementation of laws.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Development Program Resident Representative
Aeneas Chuma said at the workshop that Uganda is Africa's leading
example of progressive legislation on the protection of children's
rights.
</P>
<P>
However, more needs to be done for the rampant abuse of women
and children's rights in the country, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
