<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel to Be Set up in Nigeria for Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
has sent a draft bill to the National Assembly for the creation of
a development commission for the troubled Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Doyin Okupe said here Thursday that the
commission would enable the government to pursue the "development
needs of the area" which has recently been the scene of violent
ethnic clashes.
</P>
<P>
The commission would develop and implement a master plan for
the development of the area in the wake of agitations by local
communities alleging "marginalization" by the Nigerian government,
according to him.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo has repeatedly blamed the "neglect of the
area by previous administrations" for the recurring agitation by
youths in the oil- rich Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
The president said in an interview broadcast nationwide on
Wednesday that "the loss of confidence in government led to
frustration and anger in the Niger Delta."
</P>
<P>
During the interview, he justified the necessity for a master
plan, attributing its absence for the "wastage of funds previously
committed to the development of the area."
</P>
<P>
"We are fashioning a master plan for the development... to
ensure the money allocated for its development were judiciously
used," President Obasanjo noted.
</P>
<P>
Okupe expressed the hope that the 469-member legislature would
pass the bill to enable the president to "give effect to his
pledge to take concrete action to address the development needs of
the area."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigeria's 109-member Senate is scheduled to have a
meeting on July 6 with representatives of the country's umbrella
organization for oil industry workers in an effort to forestall a
planned industrial action by oil workers.
</P>
<P>
The strike was planned to take effect from June 28 to protest
the condition of the workers in the six multi-national oil
companies operating in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
Following the intervention of the National Assembly, the action
was postponed to enable the legislature to resolve grievances of
the workers in oil producing area of Niger Delta.
</P>
<P>
Senator Melford Okilo, chairman of a Senate ad-hoc committee on
the matter said Thursday that a seven-member delegation would
deliver the invitation to officials of the umbrella union for oil
workers.
</P>
<P>
He said that the lawmakers were compelled to "intervene because
of the importance of oil to the survival of the country", adding
that "anything that affects the sector threatens the
socio-economic and political wellbeing of the country."
</P>
<P>
Oil provides about 95 percent of the foreign exchange for the
most populous African country, which produces about 2 million
barrels of crude oil per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
