<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.N. Faces Daunting Task in Kosovo  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- When U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday was chairing an international conference on
Kosovo, foreign ministers or high-level representatives from 18
countries and three regional organizations, though dividing on
some key issues, all agreed that the post-war reconstruction in
Kosovo is enormous in scope and complex in execution.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, billed as "unprecedented" effort to organize and
support the rebuilding of Kosovo, touched upon the U.N.-led
civilian operation in the Yugoslav province -- the U.N. Interim
Administration in Kosovo (UNMIK).
</P>
<P>
As Carl Bildt, the U.N. special representative for Kosovo put
it, the issue tabled at the Wednesday meeting is about "the most
challenging and complicated mission ever undertaken by the
organization in modern times."
</P>
<P>
In other words, the task of post-war reconstruction in Kosovo
constitutes one of the largest and most ambitious such exercises
by the 185-nation United Nations.
</P>
<P>
It includes, among other things, establishing a political
system, providing police and fire services, stabilizing the
currency, delivering the mail, providing health care and even
collecting trash.
</P>
<P>
But to make a successful story in its 20-day-old operation, the
United Nations, with the help from its member states, has to cope
with immediate challenges: resettling the massive daily flow of
refugees and internally displaced persons, the establishment of a
regime of law and order and making progress in the process of
rehabilitation and reconciliation in the multi-ethnic Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Delegates said the maintenance of law and order is the priority
for Kosovo, where revenge killings broke out after tens of
thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees are returning each day.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the withdrawal of Yugoslav security forces from
Kosovo, there has been signs of growing lawlessness in Kosovo,
where revenge killings broke out in the wake of massive return of
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
At present, there appears a tendency of worsening security
condition in the province although the NATO-led peacekeepers,
known as KFOR, are being deployed.
</P>
<P>
Annan made his appeal for the swift deployment of police,
trainers and monitors to the province during a New York meeting of
"the Friends of Kosovo" -- an expanding group of nations that is
concerned about conditions in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations said it has received commitments for nearly
2,000 of the 3,110 police it wants to send to Kosovo. But Annan
said that the organization was still waiting for countries to
honor their promises.
</P>
<P>
"These are pledges," he said, "We cannot deploy and distribute
what we do not have."
</P>
<P>
A major issue still dividing countries and delaying the police
deployment is whether the civilian police should be armed. The
Netherlands said it preferred the police to be unarmed as most
U.N. civilian police are. Britain as well indicated it would have
trouble contributing to an armed police mission because the bulk
of its own police force was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
Despite the sense of urgency, Annan found himself unable to
complete the politically sensitive task of picking a candidate to
run the demanding Kosovo mission. Brazilian diplomat Sergio Vieira
de Mello is serving in that capacity on a temporary basis.
</P>
<P>
Although Annan succeeded in recruiting 1,900 international
police fo Kosovo, but he said nations still differed on how much
assistance should be given to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
"If the governments maintain that they will not provide
economic assistance or development assistance to Belgrade as long
as President (Slobodan) Milosevic is in office, and that situation
persists for a long time, then we are going to have a real
challenge of reconstructing the economy of southeastern Europe
with a big hole of Serbia in the middle," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike its previous experiences in the post-war areas, the
United Nations has to proceed its mission on the basis of the
coordination and cooperation with the European Union, the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the United Nations to undertake the
post-war reconstruction, which will surely take years in the
process, in a province of a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is also important to solicit the viewpoints from
Belgrade and involve the Yugoslav Government in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Central at issue is the respect for the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia under
the Security Council Resolution 1244, adopted by June 10.
</P>
<P>
However, some countries are intending to put Serbia, a main
republic of Yugoslavia, out of the assistance package in order to
press for the change of legitimate government in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Time is pressing, if the operation does not progress smoothly,
the international community will see one more humanitarian
catastrophe in the war-torn province in the coming winter because
many homes, together with the water-supplying system, were
destroyed by the 79-day NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
"It is pointless to take in loads and loads of medicine if
people are taking in dirty water and then get sick," Annan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
