<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Firm to Cut Jobs to Stem Rise in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- State-controlled Telkom is to
cut jobs significantly in a bid to stem the rise in net operating
costs which surged 3.5 billion rand (583 million U.S. dollars ) to
18.46 billion rand (three billion dollars) in the year to end in
March.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed in Johannesburg Thursday by Telkom Chief
Executive Officer Sizwe Nxasana when he presented the group's
financial results.
</P>
<P>
Nxasana said that since April Telkom had shed some 2,000 of its
61,000 employees through early retirement. It was also looking to
exit from non-core business and outsource work where possible.
</P>
<P>
Nxasana also disclosed that the rise in Telkom's operating
costs had been greater than the comparable increase in revenue
received and that, with planned restructuring, costs would be even
higher in the current financial year.
</P>
<P>
Telkom has embarked on a wide-ranging efficiency and
cost-containment drive to "trim wastage and duplication on an
unprecedented scale."
</P>
<P>
It said its start-point during 1998-99 had been to clamp down
on "unnecessary expenses, including travel and subsistence
allowances, and tighten up controls on the use of vehicles and
other equipment."
</P>
<P>
But the Telkom chief said if these measures did not meet
requirements, then the telecommunications company would have to
introduce a complete retrenchment program.
</P>
<P>
Nxasana, however, declined to say how many jobs the company was
going to cut. "We have a figure in mind. But it is confidential,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
There have been rumors that the group was looking at trimming
its labor force to around 50,000.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995 Telkom's staff complement has fallen from almost
59,000 to 56, 480 in 1998. But by March this year it had climbed
to 61,237.
</P>
<P>
It has however embraced the transformation process and in the
past five years the composition of its work force has changed from
being 54 percent white and 46 percent black to 59 percent black
and 41 percent white.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the increase in the group's net operating costs,
Nxasana said this was directly related to Telkom's decision to
invest heavily in its national infrastructure to ensure it could
improve on the level of service provided to new and existing
customers both in the short term and in the years ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Firm to Cut Jobs to Stem Rise in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nxasana said, "Retaining and growing our customer base is what
it is all about. The lack of ongoing maintenance in previous years
had led to the steady deterioration of our network, exposing
customers to seasonal, weather- related service disruptions.
</P>
<P>
"Realizing that the state of our network posed a liability,
both in terms of service and quality and our long-term efficiency,
we began investing heavily in network rehabilitation almost three
years ago."
</P>
<P>
"This rehabilitation drive reached a peak during the period
under review when Telkom spent 1.436 billion rand (239 million
dollars) on network rehabilitation, 632.7 million rand (105
million dollars) more than in 1997- 98", he added.
</P>
<P>
Nxasana said he had budgeted for capital spending of 10 billion
rand (1.6 billion dollars) in the current financial year.
</P>
<P>
"Our initiatives to restructure and transform the company for
competition will be accelerated during 1999-2000 and will
therefore be reflected in higher costs associated with
restructuring for the year," he said. "This will in turn have an
impact on our net income for 1999-2000 which we expect will be
significantly lower than in 1998-99."
</P>
<P>
He added: "Our share-holders fully support our drive to
position ourselves for competition well before it is introduced,
even if this requires a short- term drop in net income."
</P>
<P>
Telkom said that during the financial year it had provided
502,750 new telephone lines, 42,750 more than its license
requirements.
</P>
<P>
During the year, 920 villages went on-line for the first time,
27,271 new pay phones were installed and there were new
connections for 4,774 priority customers - hospitals, clinics and
schools.
</P>
<P>
Nxasana said Telkom was committed to providing a better quality
service for all sectors of South African society.
</P>
<P>
"Telkom," he also stated, "remains fully committed to meeting
the vast and changing telecommunications needs of the South
African business community and will not sacrifice its efforts to
service one key customer group at the expense of another." 
</P>
