<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Conference Ends Demanding Science for Peace and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 1 (Xinhua)--After six days of debates and
discussions, the World Conference on Science ended on Thursday
with two documents calling for employing science and technology
for the peace and welfare of the world.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 scientists, officials and other stakeholders in
science and education from 150 countries all over the world
accepted the "Declaration on Science and The Use of Scientific
Knowledge" and the "Science Agenda-Framework for Action".
</P>
<P>
The two documents were issued by the U.N. Educational,
Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) that held the
conference together with the International Council of Science
Unions (ICSU).
</P>
<P>
"You have deployed so much energy over the last six days and
contributed to so many important debates, that our final documents
can truly be said to result from...a highly interactive process,"
Federico Mayor, Director-General of the UNESCO and chairman of the
conference, expressed his satisfaction to the participants in the
conference at his final address.
</P>
<P>
Amid the rapid progress of science during the 20th century and
an even explosive one in the next, the documents called on
scientists and scientific policy-makers to concentrate their
endeavors for a peaceful world and the well-being of human
society, but not for high-tech armaments.
</P>
<P>
"This is a crucial time for science," said Mayor, adding:"our
professional activities are more than just jobs-underlying them is
a mission--to improve the lives of human beings."
</P>
<P>
Too many times during the out-going century, people have wasted
scientific findings and technical breakthroughs in wars, conflicts
and weapons, he said at an earlier interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The resolution documents, which will be later sent to the U.N.
General Assembly for adoption, urged governments to aim their
research projects specifically at addressing the basic needs of
population. Moreover, it urged the industrialized countries to
help the poor ones in scientific and technical projects.
</P>
<P>
Also, the documents urged all parts of the society, not only
the scientists, to make and fulfill commitments for more healthy
development and better employment of scientific knowledge.
Governmental leaders, educational experts, enterpreneurs and media
staff should make up a "big alliance" for the goal, Mayor said.
</P>
<P>
The importance of ethic standards in scientific issues were
fully recognized at by the delegates to the conference. At the
final documents, the delegates to Budapest called scientists to
take responsibility for world's peace and development, and to
respect the dignity of human beings in their research works.
</P>
<P>
Topics such as intellectual property rights, women's role in
science, science education, and the popularization of science were
also accepted into the final documents as most important issues.
</P>
<P>
As a partial success, some of the world's poorest nations added
their demands into the resolutions, which urged to fund the
scientific projects in the most undeveloped countries to be funded
with the resources freed by debt relief.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, though strongly against by the rich nations,
was appreciated by delegates from Africa and the Islamic world,
and was hailed as the greatest achievement of the conference.
</P>
<P>
"We have it in our power to contribute to the well-being and
the human dignity of people who will never hear of conference, but
whose lives we can improve." said Mayor.
</P>
<P>
"And now, as we split up and go our separate ways, we take with
us a shared determination...And even after we separate, we remain
joined by a shared-by a new-commitment." he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
