<HEADLINE> Clinton, Mubarak Hold Talks on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and U.S. President Bill Clinton started their talks at the White
House on how to revive the Middle East peace process as Israel's
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak was forming a new government to
give a new momentum for the peace course.
</P>
<P>
"The primary agenda items for the president's meeting with
President Mubarak will be the Middle East peace process," White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"they will discuss their own shared vision for how to move the
process forward," he added.
</P>
<P>
The "shared vision" was based on the Oslo and Wye River peace
accords between Israel and the Palestinians, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton aims to meet with Barak once his government is in place
and "getting the peace process back on track," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders first started their one-to-one meeting and were
then to be joined by their aides later. After the talks they will
hold a joint news conference.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss regional issues including Iraq and
Iran, as well as bilateral matters including U.S. efforts to
bolster Egypt's economy, Lockhart said. 
</P>
