<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Today's Diplomatic News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua today:
</P>
<P>
 Chinese, Namibian Presidents Hold Talks
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, in talks here today with Namibia
's President Sam Nujoma, said that China treasures its friendship
with Namibia and is willing to carry more solid and friendly
bilateral ties into the new century through a joint effort.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that humanity is right now at a critical period for
global peace and common development, and some of the major tasks
around the world are opposing hegemony and power politics and
promoting the establishment of a just and rational new
international political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates the fact that Namibia upholds justice on the
global scene and has a particularly clear-cut stand on some
critical issues,added Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said that the interference of Western countries has
further complicated the situation in Africa, a continent beset by
difficulties, continuous conflicts, and civil wars.
</P>
<P>
As hegemony continues, the industrialized countries sabotage
the unity and cooperation among developing countries, he said,
adding that African nations and the Organization of African Unity
are making an attempt to oppose foreign interference and put and
end to regional conflicts and civil wars and anticipate a UN role
as well as China's support.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Premier Meets Cambodian Senior Minister
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said today that China and Cambodia
should reinforce bilateral cooperation in various fields to bring
traditional Sino-Cambodian friendship up to a new level.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the statement during a meeting with Hor Nam Hong,
Cambodia's senior minister and minister of foreign affairs and
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China values its economic and trade ties with Cambodia on the
basis of equality and mutual benefit and it is willing to provide
support and help to the economic reconstruction in Cambodia within
China's ability, Zhu told Hor Nam Hong.
</P>
<P>
 Summary of FM Spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue's Remarks
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan FM to Visit China
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart
Kemelevich Tokayev of the Republic of Kazakhstan will pay an
official visit to China from July 7 to 15.
</P>
<P>
 China's Stand on Entering WTO Unchanged
</P>
<P>
China's stand on entering the World Trade Organization (WTO)
remains unchanged, Zhang said, adding: "Due to the attack on the
Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia by the U.S.-led NATO, the Sino-U.S.
relationship has encountered some difficulties."
</P>
<P>
 U.S. Urged to Compensate
</P>
<P>
China urged the United States to make rapid, comprehensive and
effective compensation for casualties and property losses during
the U.S.-led NATO bomb attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
The two sides will discuss compensation issues through diplomatic
channels, according to Zhang.  
</P>
</TEXT>
