<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Economy in Slow Growth: U.N. Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite some short-term
favorable developments, global economic growth in 1999 "remains
inadequate and markedly lower than at mid-decade", particularly
for most developing countries, a U.N. report said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Experts of the U.N. Department of Economic and Social Affairs
said world output is forecast to grow 2 percent in 1999 against
1.9 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries as a group are predicted to rise 1.75
percent compared to 2 percent in 1998, developing economies are
expected to go up 2.5 percent from 1.7 percent and transition
economies covering former Eastern Europe are foreseen to decline
0.50 percent from a positive 0.2 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the report of "The World Economy in 1999" to the
press, U.N. Under-Secretary-General for Economic and Social
Affairs Nitin Desai said the financial crises of the past two
years and ensuing economic slowdowns "have dealt a stunning blow
to world development prospects".
</P>
<P>
The resport suggests that a growth rate of 3% annually needs to
be sustained to allow progress in raising living standards and
reducing poverty.
</P>
<P>
Only 13 developing countries are forecast to grow enough to
meet that benchmark in 1999, compared to 39 in 1996, the year
immediately before the global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The 31-page report is on the agenda of the high-level meeting
in Geneva from July 5-30 of the U.N. Economic and Social Council.
</P>
<P>
The analysis follows a letter form U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan to the June Group of 8 Summit in Cologne, Germany, calling
on leading industrialized countries to take measures to increase
world economic growth, shore up international financial structures
and take greater account of the need of the poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
