<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Threatens to Sue EU Over Gene Corn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Environmental protection group,
Greenpeace, is threatening to sue the European Union (EU) if the
bloc's executive body, the European Commission, failed to withdraw
authorizations for genetically modified corn in the 15 EU member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Greenpeace took the step because researchers at Cornell
University found in May that the hybrid crop, known as Bt-maize,
produced pollen that could harm the larvae of the monarch
butterfly. Bt-maize has been developed to protect maize from
attacks by the corn borer pest.
</P>
<P>
In respond to the research result, the European Commission said
it would block the approval of another Bt-maize developed by U.S.
company Pioneer Hi-Bred International, but also said similar crops
already being marketed by Monsanto Co and Novartis AG, the two
European companies, would not be immediately affected.
</P>
<P>
"The commission's logic is skewed," Greenpeace biotechnology
campaigner Thomas Schweiger said in a statement. "It is not taking
action on the already approved lines of Bt-maize even though it is
obvious that the products already out there present much greater
risk than the ones in the pipeline."
</P>
<P>
The environmental group said it would consider legal action if
the EU executive failed to act. The Greenpeace said it has sent
the commission a legal opinion demanding that the already approved
Bt-maize products must be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
EU environmental ministers last week reached an initial
agreement on revisions to the bloc's approval system for new
genetically modified organisms (GMOs).
</P>
<P>
They agreed that they would probably not approve any more GMOs
until the new rules are up and running. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
