<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Talks First Step to Improve Ties, Says Greek </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Talks between Greek and Turkish
Foreign Ministers in New York were "a first step" to seek ways to
cooperate on a number of issues, Greek government spokesman
Yiannis Nikolaou said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Nikolaou said that there should
not be either great optimism or great pessimism.
</P>
<P>
Following talks with his Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem, Greek
Foreign Minister George Papandreou said that there was room for
bilateral cooperation between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey on Wednesday agreed to hold talks on a
Foreign Ministry senior officials level on issues concerning the
economy, trade, environment, tourism, as well as combating
organized crime, illegal immigration, drugs and on law and order
issues, and once the potential for cooperation was ascertained,
the two countries would proceed further.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the New York talks, Greece's main opposition New
Democracy (ND) on Thursday said in a statement that the ND backed
the normalization of Greece's relations with Turkey, but the
dialogue between the two countries must be held under conditions
such as the halt by Turkey to make territorial claims, the
abandonment of the threat of using force and the respect for
international law and existing treaties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Greek Prime Minister Constantine Mitsotakis
also voiced his support for the government's dialogue with Turkey,
however, he stressed that such dialogue had to be conducted in a
specific framework.
</P>
<P>
The road to an improvement in Greek-Turkish relations could
open at the same time as substantial progress on the issue or
Cyprus, which was necessary for any attempt at rapprochement
between the two countries to be lasting and continuous, he added.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Greece and Turkey have been strained over
decades for their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits, the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece has repeatedly said that relations between the two
countries can only improve step-by-step and if Turkey believes
there are issues which are unsettled, it can seek recourse to the
International Court of Justice at the Hague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
