<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams Turkey for Extending Operation Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Thursday slammed Turkey's
decision to extend the presence of western air force in Turkish
air bases for patrolling northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry spokesman told the Iraqi News Agency that
the Turkish parliament has approved the extension of the force,
codenamed Operation Norther Watch, in Turkish bases for another
six months as from June 30.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Iraq holds the Turkish government responsible
for the possible aggression by the force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The force, established by the U.S.-led western allies in 1991
after the Gulf War, uses Turkish air base to monitor the northern
no-fly zone in Iraq, carved up unilaterally by the allied forces
with a claimed aim of protecting the Kurds there from possible
attacks by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
The allied forces also use air bases in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait
to patrol another no-fly zone set up in southern Iraq claimedly to
protect the Shiite Muslims there.
</P>
<P>
Since the United States and Britain launched airstrikes against
Iraq last December, Baghdad has been denying the two no-fly zones,
saying they were not sanctioned by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Skirmishes between Iraqi air defense force and the western
warplanes have become regular occurrence in the two zones ever
since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICRC Urges Governments to Strengthen Arms Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) has called on governments to limit the
uncontrolled proliferation of arms and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
"The current pattern of transfers of small arms, light weapons
and related ammunition, because it is largely outside
international control, should be a matter of urgent humanitarian
concern," said ICRC President Cornelio Sommaruga here Thursday
when launching an ICRC report entitled "Arms Availability and the
Situation of Civilians in Armed Conflict".
</P>
<P>
"We call on states to review their policies concerning the
production, availability and transfer of arms and ammunition in
light of their responsibility to 'respect and ensure respect' for
the international humanitarian law," he went on.
</P>
<P>
In the report, the ICRC blamed the uncontrolled proliferation
of arms and ammunition for "increasing tension in the world's
trouble spots, prolonging conflicts and undermining the laws that
protect civilians in time of war".
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-based humanitarian organization warned of the
disastrous effects on civilian populations of uncontrolled
transfer and misuse of weapons.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the number of manufacturers of small arms
is estimated to have increased by 25 percent between 1985 and
1995. Furthermore, it said, large quantities of weapons were sold
or given away as the world's big military powers reduced their
stocks after the end of the Cold War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
