<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Congo (K) Peace Talks Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Nothing has come out from the
on-going ministerial meeting on ending the 11-month conflict in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) for a third day running
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which started Monday attended by defense, home and
foreign affairs ministers from the 14 Southern African Development
Community (SADC) member states, as well as from Rwanda, Uganda and
Libya, discussed a draft document on a cease-fire in Congo (K) by
a technical committee.
</P>
<P>
The draft document was reported to call for a cease-fire from
July 3, deployment of peace-keepers in the DRC, withdrawal of
foreign armies and disarming of rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting told Xinhua on condition of
anonymity Thursday that disagreement remained over some main
points in the draft document.
</P>
<P>
If discussion by the ministers are eventually successful, heads
of state from the region will gather here to put their signatures
to the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
Officials said they were optimistic that a deal could be struck
finally. However, a quick breakthrough is not realistic, they
added.
</P>
<P>
Participants attending the peace talks disclosed that the
meeting had been temporarily put off to allow the belligerents to
resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
It was said rebels were still divided over who should lead in
the talks and which one is the main group.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, for the first time, is understood to have been
attended by leaders of the three rebel groups fighting to oust
Congolese President Laurent Kabila's government: Wamba dia Wamba's
Rally for Congolese Democracy (RCD), Jean Pierre Bemba's Movement
for the Liberation of Congo (MLC) and Emile Ilunga's Goma-based
RCD splinter group.
</P>
<P>
Wamba insists that his is the main group and "the splinter
group should have no mandate at the talks", while Ilunga said his
group would not accept Wamba to attend any meeting because he "has
no mandate of the Congolese people or the RCD".
</P>
<P>
In turn, the Goma-based RCD also calls Wamba's group as a
splinter, and threatened to walk out of the Lusaka talks should
Wamba be allowed to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's meeting of belligerents when Wamba arrived, the
Goma- based RCD faction led by Ilunga walked out immediately.
</P>
<P>
Conference sources said other areas for contention were rebel
demands to negotiate a new political structure in the country,
which is rejected by the government. The rebels also insist that
all foreign forces be withdrawn simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
But the contentious issues are reported to hinge on the
timetable for withdrawal of foreign forces and the mandate of the
joint military council that is supposed to oversee the
implementation of the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The Kabila government demands a full control of the country
soon after the cease-fire pact is adopted while the rebels prefer
holding on to the territory now under their control as
negotiations on political reforms continue.
</P>
<P>
Congolese Foreign Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia said control of
the country' s territory after the cease-fire agreement was an
internal matter that should not be on the agenda of the Lusaka
talks.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the hitches at the talks, Yerodia said this was
normal in such talks. "There is a delay, yes, but we did not come
here just to say 'Okay and good-bye.' This conflict has been going
on for two years and you don't expect us to come and finish it so
soon."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SADC Secretary-General Kaire Mbuende said the delay
is mainly "on full stops and commas".
</P>
<P>
"But we are almost through now. It might take sometime but we
are optimistic that we will finish," Mbuende stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
