<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Sticks to Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud
Thursday renewed his country's commitment to adhere to the
five-nation committee monitoring a truce agreement in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon is committed to the letter and spirit of the April
Understanding and refuse any attempts for amendment or
modifications of it,"he said when meeting with the country's
parliament members.
</P>
<P>
The committee, made up of representatives from the United
States, France, Syria, Israel and Lebanon, was established after
Israel and Lebanon reached a truce agreement in April 1996 which
ended a 16-day Israeli blitz on Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The committee was due to convene on Tuesday to discuss 14
complaints filed by Lebanon and 21 by Israel after a 10-hour
Israeli air strike on Lebanon late June 24 which killed eight
Lebanese and wounded 64 and destroyed the country's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon accused Israel of violating terms of the accord and
targetting civilians while Israel argued that its operations
came in retaliation to Hezbollah's cross-border Katyusha attacks
which killed two Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, is fighting
to oust Israeli troops out of south Lebanon where the Jewish
state set up a self-declared security zone in 1985 as a
buffer zone to protect its north.
</P>
<P>
But, the planned panel meeting was suspended by outgoing
Israeli Defense Minister Moshe Arens who said Israel would
participate again in the meeting after the Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak forms his government next week.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli move sparked Lebanese government's concern that
Israel will abort the accord which Lebanon said could protect
civilians and Arens dismissed as useless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
