<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Set Up New Office to Manage Public Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will set up a
new office to be in charge of managing the country's public debts
which have increased by about 50 percent over the past six months,
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin said Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai agreed with his
proposal to set up the special office, aimed at helping manage
public debts more efficiently by bringing all separately existing
agencies involved in public debt management under the sole control
of the newly-established organ, Thai News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Thailand's public debts are under the supervision of
many agencies.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's public debts stood at 1.77 trillion baht (47.84
billion U.S. dollars) as of June 30, compared to 1.16 trillion
baht (31.35 billion dollars) as of the end of last year. The debts
are the government's foreign borrowings used to support economic
reforms and rehabilitation after the Thai economy was hard hit by
the financial crisis which began two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The new office will examine the government's capability of debt
servicing and risk management, as well as fluctuations of interest
rates and exchange rates and the scheduling of the debt repayment,
said Tarrin.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's foreign exchange reserves, which measure the
government's foreign debt repayment capability, stood at 31
billion dollars as of June 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
