<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Foreign Exchange Stands Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's foreign exchange market,
hit by shortages in April, appeared to be firm during the past
week on the back of foreign currency inflows from the country's
premier crop, tobacco.
</P>
<P>
The market, which has been in shortages for the greatest part
of the past two months, improved dramatically during the past
week from a deficit of 5.1 million U.S. dollars on June 24 to a
deficit of 600,000 U.S. dollars Wednesday, the Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its weekly foreign exchange report for the week ending June
30, the central bank said the level of forex inflows was almost
balanced with inflows of 51.5 million U.S. dollars and outflows
of 50.1 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The past week recorded the highest inflows of 12.5 million U.S.
dollars on June 30 with the highest outflows on June 24 at 13.1
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the currency front, the Zimbabwean dollar continued stable
trading at between 37.95 and 37.96 against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
