<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Post Big Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets rocketed to
sharply higher closes Thursday after the U.S. Federal Reserve's
decision to hike interest rates by a quarter point to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Stock markets normally fall back when interest rates go up, but
investors had been expecting this rise - and were pleased that the
Fed indicated that it was not planning to raise interest rates
again soon.
</P>
<P>
London shares surged 170.4 points, their biggest single-session
point gain in nearly six months. The FTSE-100 Index closed up 2.7
percent at 6488.9.
</P>
<P>
Interest-rate sensitive banking stocks were cheered by the
Fed's decision and made a healthy contribution to the Footsie's
strong gains on the first day of the new quarter.
</P>
<P>
HSBC shares soared 119p, or 5 percent, to 2366p while NatWest
jumped 59p to 1404p, Royal Bank of Scotland rose 40p to 1332p and
Standard Chartered finished up 44p at 1080p.
</P>
<P>
Germany's benchmark share index, the Xetra Dax, advanced 101.70
points, or 1.89 percent, to 5480.22 amid sharp strides in the
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
But strong economic data in the United States triggered fears
of further hikes, dampening the mood on the Dax and braking its
advance past the 5500 resistance level.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index ended up 1.6 percent at 4609.26
points - putting its rise so far this year at 17 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
