<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Still Optimistic About N. Ireland Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday said that Northern Ireland parties were determined to
break the deadlock in their peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told a news conference at the White House that he had
been "in virtually constant contact" with parties to the Belfast
talks.
</P>
<P>
"They are in negotiations as we speak and the mood seems to
be reasonably positive," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"They are exploring some new ideas and they do seem determined
to work it through to a positive conclusion," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president also said he had offered his own ideas on how to
break the deadlock over the key issues of the timing of guerrilla
disarmament and the formation of a power-sharing provincial
government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Clinton spoke to British Prime Minister
Tony Blair for a third time in 24 hours to discuss the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that the president
remained ready to lend a hand to nudge the talks forward if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"The president again made the point that both he and the United
States government stands ready to intercede and help in any way
that they can," Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Clinton also spoke by telephone with Northern
Ireland's main Protestant leader David Trimble and Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Clinton urged all political parties in Northern
Ireland to "give peace a chance" as they worked against a midnight
deadline to save the Good Friday peace pact.
</P>
<P>
"I will do whatever I can to be helpful. We're moving forward
and I'm hoping for the best," Clinton said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
