<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Tying Gold Production To Global Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The deputy director of the State
Economic and Trade Commission's Gold Bureau, Cheng Fumin, says
that China's gold industry needs to be more aware of the market
and be ready to confront market challenges to maintain healthy
growth.
</P>
<P>
Cheng told the opening ceremony of the Daye Gold Mine in the
city of Rushan in Shandong Province today that the situation the
gold industry faces is the most serious since China started its
reforms and opening up in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The international gold price has dropped to the lowest point in
the past two decades, as gold reserves are sold off by central
banks in many countries. China has been speeding up the process of
entering the international market with a gold management system
and the Bank of China cut the price of gold twice in May and June.
</P>
<P>
The price is now 71.64 yuan a gram (8.6 U.S. dollars), a drop
of 15 percent as China reacted to changes in the international
gold market, Cheng says, explaining that a world-market-oriented
price system has essentially been established in China as an
unavoidable step. China's gold companies need to watch the trends
in international gold prices closely to adjust to them.
</P>
<P>
China will support several big gold companies that are expected
to head up the industry and to make it more competitive in the
world.
</P>
<P>
China produced 172.8 tons of gold last year and had a billion
yuan (120 million U.S. dollars) in profits. It plans to produce
175 tons this year and announced a slowdown in production at the
beginning of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
