<HEADLINE> India Says No Widening of Conflict In Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI July 2 (Xinhua) -- India said Friday that there was
no widening of the on-going conflict with Pakistan in Kashmir
though there was no evidence of Pakistan withdrawing its troops
and "extremists" from the Indian side of the line of control
(LoC).
</P>
<P>
An External Affairs Ministry spokesman told a news briefing
that Pakistan was making "desperate attempts" to replenish
supplies to the "intruders" who were being systematically pushed
back.
</P>
<P>
"There is no evidence on the ground that Pakistan is
withdrawing its forces from the remaining pockets of intrusion on
our side of the LoC," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He urged Islamabad to withdraw its "armed intruders" from the
Indian side of the LoC, after which he said the question of
resumption of the Lahore process could be taken up.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi has insisted that there be no further talks with
Pakistan before the "intruders" are cleared out of the Kargil
sector in the disputed Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
An Indian army spokesman said at the briefing that fierce
fighting was going on to evict the "intruders" from the strategic
"Tiger Hill" overlooking the crucial Srinagar-Leh highway in
Drass, another battle ground in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He said that while the enemy had been evicted completely from
one position and partially from another, a foothold was yet to be
achieved at the other three or four locations in Batalik sector.
</P>
<P>
In the last 24 hours, he said, seven Pakistan soldiers had been
killed, taking the toll of Pakistani army regulars to 446, while
217 Indian troops had been killed, as many as 406 wounded and nine
were missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
