<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua here today:
</P>
<P>
 Sino-Namibian Ties Hailed
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, chairman of the Chinese National People's Congress (
NPC) Standing Committee, and Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, met with
Namibia's President Sam Nujoma respectively here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng said that China and Namibia have a traditional
friendship and their cooperation in different areas has been
reinforced since the establishment of diplomatic ties nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The NPC and Namibian parliament have a good relationship, which
has increased mutual understanding between the people of the two
developing countries, Li said, and the NPC is ready to increase
exchanges and cooperation with the Namibian parliament.
</P>
<P>
Namibia is now building a democratic system in accordance with
its own characteristics, said Nujoma, adding that the system is
not a copy of a Western style but is intended to let Namibians
enjoy equal rights.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Nujoma, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
expressed the willingness to fully tap the economic and trade
cooperative potential between China and Namibia through concerted
efforts.
</P>
<P>
He pledged on behalf of the State Council to seriously
implement the agreements reached during yesterday's successful
talks between presidents of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Namibia enjoys abundant resources, and there's strong
complementary and broad potential for the future economic and
trade cooperation between the two countries, Nujoma replied.
</P>
<P>
Namibia welcomes more Chinese enterprises to invest there and
the Namibian Government would offer support for them with good
conditions, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian met today with his
Namibian counterpart Erikki Nghimtina, who accompanied Nujoma in
his visit to China. Chi said that the Chinese People's Liberation
Army (PLA) is fully prepared to increase exchanges and cooperation
with the Namibian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Japanese PM to Visit China
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan will pay an official visit
to China from July 8 to 10 at the invitation of Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
 Cambodian Senior Minister Continues China Visit
</P>
<P>
Hor Nam Hong, Cambodia's senior minister and minister of
Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation, left here this
morning for Shanghai to continue his China visit.
</P>
<P>
 Talks Between DPRK and ROK Suspended
</P>
<P>
The vice-ministerial talks between the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea and the Republic of Korea were suspended today
for the profound differences between the two sides on a number of
issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides differed on the agenda on separated families'
reunion in the talks, as well as the naval skirmishes in the
disputed waters on the Yellow Sea and the ROK's fertilizer aid to
the DPRK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
