<HEADLINE> France Urges Israel to Return to Lebanon Truce Committee Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- France Friday called on Israel to
return to the meeting of the Truce Surveillance Committee in
Southern Lebanon after Israel's new Prime Minister Ehud Barak has
formed his government.
</P>
<P>
Israel boycotted a meeting of the committee previously
scheduled for this week.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry vice spokesman Francois Rivasseau said
that the committee had helped save hundreds of lives and greatly
reduced the tension in southern Lebanon since its creation in
August 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The committee has over the past several years calmed down the
situation which was once very tense (in southern Lebanon), due to
the good will of the parties present and the efforts of the Franco-
U.S. co-presidency," he said.
</P>
<P>
The committee consists of France, the United States, Syria,
Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The United States has also expressed its intention to continue
working for the committee despite Israel's boycott.
</P>
<P>
"The United States government supports totally the pursuit of
the work of the surveillance committee in charge of supervising
the implementation of the April 1996 truce agreement, because it
provides the most efficient mechanism for tackling the tension and
protecting civilians in southern Lebanon," said U.S. ambassador to
Lebanon, David Satterfield, in Beirut on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
France called for a meeting of the committee after Israel
launched air raids against Lebanon two weeks ago, killing eight
people and injuring 62.
</P>
<P>
Israel said it was taking revenge for the rocket attacks by
Shiite Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas in southern Lebanon, which
killed two Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
