<HEADLINE> Euro Reference Rate Slips to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Euro's reference rate slipped
Friday to a record low of 1.0241 U.S. dollars, two tenths of a
cent off Thursday's 1.0264 dollars, according to the European
Central Bank (ECB) in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
That meant the dollar would buy 1.9098 German Mark, up from
Thursday's 1.9055 marks.
</P>
<P>
The ECB set reference rates for the euro of 0.64980 pounds
sterling (0.65020) 123.93 yen (124.12) and 1.6060 Swiss francs
(1.6043) (Thursday reference rates in brackets).
</P>
<P>
On the Frankfurt Stock Exchange, Thursday's rally petered out
and the main index, the DAX was up just 2.82 points at 2 p.m. to
5480.04 amid very mixed trading. Secondary stocks improved,
pushing the 70- stock M-DAX up 10.51 points to 4067.01.
</P>
<P>
European stock prices were held back by signs of a continuing
economic boom in the United States that was "wrecking the illusion
that only one interest-rate hike will be enough to cool it off".
</P>
<P>
"The minute the interest-rate scare evaporates, it comes back
again," said one trader ruefully.
</P>
<P>
Automobile stocks were among those that performed worst Friday,
with BMW easing 1.71 per cent to 686 euros and Volkswagen hit by
rumours that analysts were recommending the stock be sold. VW fell
2.92 per cent to 61.55 euros as a result.
</P>
<P>
Thyssen-Krupp stock beat the pessimism, rising 2.3 per cent to
22.20 euros, while Lufthansa jumped 1.24 per cent to 18.02 euros.
</P>
<P>
On the Frankfurt bond market, prices eased as much as 2.42
percentage points and the Bundesbank's Umlauf yield rose 14 base
points to 4.33 per cent. The Euro Bund Future rate was off 26
points by 2 p.m. to 109.54.  
</P>
</TEXT>
