<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Edges up Slightly to 4.3 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said Friday
that the U.S. unemployment rate edged up only 0.1 percent to 4.3
percent in June as factories continued to shed jobs.
</P>
<P>
The rate still remained at the lowest levels in nearly three
decades, even though the May unemployment rate of 4.2 percent was
a 29-year low.
</P>
<P>
In June, manufacturing jobs decreased by another 35,000,
bringing the total job loss at factories since March 1998 to
488,000. Manufacturing has been the hardest hit sector from the
global financial crisis, because of a loss of major export markets
overseas and increasing competition from cheap imports.
</P>
<P>
However, employment at U.S. businesses accelerated sharply last
month with a total of 268,000 new jobs created with all industries
except manufacturing and mining posting solid gains.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,
increased by 3.7 percent in June, compared to a year ago, to 13.23
dollars. This was up only slightly from the May increase.
</P>
<P>
The declines in manufacturing jobs were widespread last month,
led by large job losses at aircraft factories and plants making
electrical equipment and apparel. Employment in the apparel
industry has fallen by one-third since November 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Department said mining also saw further job declines in
June, losing 3,000 jobs while job losses in oil and gas drilling
lessened during the month.
</P>
<P>
But construction, which had suffered big job losses in May,
rebounded last month, posting a gain of 26,000 jobs with plumbing,
electrical work and roofing all showing increases.
</P>
<P>
The overall gain of 268,000 payroll jobs was led by strong
hiring at amusement parks. Also posting big gains were retail
trade, which added 49,000 jobs in June, bringing total job growth
in this sector to 265,000 through the first half of this year. The
largest gain of last month came from hiring at restaurants and
bars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Act to Protect Industrial Designs Adopted by Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A new act to broaden the
geographical scope of international industrial design protection
was adopted by consensus here Friday at the end of the diplomatic
conference of the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO).
</P>
<P>
WIPO Director General Kamil Idris welcomed the successful
conclusion of the Geneva Act of the Hague Agreement Concerning
International Registration of Industrial Designs, which became
effective in 1960.
</P>
<P>
"We are delighted with the outcome of the diplomatic conference
and the positive spirit of cooperation that prevailed throughout
the talks and resulted in consensus on all the issues discussed,"
said Idris.
</P>
<P>
The new act, the WIPO head said, will help fulfill the
tremendous potential of the Hague system by offering an even more
flexible, cost-effective and user-friendly means for companies and
individuals across the globe to protect their industrial designs.
</P>
<P>
The new act, expected to enter into force after six
ratifications of over 80 contracting parties, introduces a number
of important changes to the Hague system for the registration of
industrial designs, according to WIPO.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva act enhances the existing system for the
international registration of industrial designs by making it more
compatible with the registration systems in countries such as the
United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
One of the main advantages of using the Hague system is that it
allows users to include up to as many as 100 designs in each
international application that is made.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, WIPO registered about 4,000 international deposits
each covering on average 11 countries. This represented a 40
percent increase on the number deposited 10 years previously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's External Trade Volume Down in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The volume of Hong Kong's re-
exports in April 1999 fell by 2.7 percent over a year earlier, and
that of domestic exports by 14.1 percent, according to statistics
released by the Census and Statistics Department here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Taken together, the volume of total exports decreased by 4.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the volume of imports dropped by 11.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the first four months of 1999 with the same period a
year earlier, the volume of Hong Kong's re-exports fell by 3.7
percent, and the volume of domestic exports by 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Taken together, the volume of total exports during the period
dropped by 4.6 percent. Meanwhile, imports fell by 10.6 percent in
volume.
</P>
<P>
Comparing April 1999 with April 1998, the prices of re-exports
and domestic exports fell by 4.0 percent and 3.0 percent
respectively. Import prices also declined, by 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
As regards price changes in the first four months of 1999 over
the same period a year earlier, the prices of re-exports and
domestic exports were down by 4.4 percent and 2.7 percent
respectively, and import prices by 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ian K Perkin, chief economist of the Hong Kong General Chamber
of Commerce, said these figures showed Hong Kong's external trade
still being affected by both lower global prices and trade volumes.
</P>
<P>
But the declines in export volumes and prices were more than
offset by a big drop in import volume, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
