<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak, Arafat Agree to Meet Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman
Yasser Arafat agreed Friday to meet soon after Barak takes office
next week, Barak's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister-elect and Arafat agreed to arrange a
meeting shortly after the government is presented to the Knesset
(parliament)," local media quoted spokesman David Ziso as saying.
</P>
<P>
In his telephone conversations with Arafat, Barak also
reiterated his determination to continue along the path of late
Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin and put the stalled peace
process back on track, Ziso said.
</P>
<P>
No date being set, the forthcoming meeting would be the first
Israeli-Palestinian summit in nearly seven months. Arafat met with
outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in mid-December in a
three-way summit with United States President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Barak released a statement calling Arafat "an
important and central partner" for peace, saying he would like to
meet with him soon.
</P>
<P>
The victory of moderate Barak in the May elections has raised
hope of reviving the Middle East peace process, which was largely
frozen during the tenure of the hard-line government of Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Barak will present to the parliament next week a governing
coalition he put together through six weeks of grueling talks with
other parliamentary parties.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have hailed "a new era of peacemaking" after
Barak secured a 75-seat majority in the 120-member parliament for
his emerging government.
</P>
<P>
Since Barak has pledged to reinvigorate the peace process in
all tracks, including the Syrian and Lebanon tracks, the
Palestinians have expressed fear that he might prefer to talk
with Syria and Lebanon first and left their problems behind.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said Arafat had complained that Barak did not
phone him after his election victory while exchanging indirect
messages with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, Barak issued a statement Friday
saying his government would ensure the unity of and Israel's
sovereignty over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to remarks made by a dovish Labor legislator
who said he would not oppose to Palestinian flags flying on the
Temple Mount, a holy site in the city.
</P>
<P>
Yossi Beilin, an architect of the 1993 Oslo peace accords,
confirmed reports that he would agree to the idea of Palestinian
flags being raised on the Al-Aqsa Mosque, a Muslim shrine in the
Arab East Jerusalem, saying this "symbolic and religious" matter
would be accepted by all.
</P>
<P>
The right-wing Likud called on Barak to condemn Beilin's
remarks, which it termed as "grave."
</P>
<P>
Israel annexed Arab East Jerusalem after seizing it from
Jordan's control in the 1967 Middle East war. The Palestinians
want East Jerusalem as capital of their future state.
</P>
<P>
Barak holds the same line on the issue of Jerusalem, claiming
it would remain the "eternal and undivided capital" of Israel
under a permanent peace agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Beilin acknowledged that he discussed the flag issue during
his secret talks with senior Palestinian official Abu Mazen in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the two had reached a draft agreement on the
future of Jerusalem, under which the Palestinians would agree to
build its capital at Abu Dis, an Arab village just outside East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
