<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts New Standards for State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China has announced that it will
adopt international practices in assessing the performance of
state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to facilitate reforms.
</P>
<P>
The new standards involve using return on net assets as an
index of performance to encourage them to concentrate resources on
the core business and discourage them from over-diversifying.
</P>
<P>
The new standards come from the Ministry of Finance, which says
that they address the shortcomings of the previous means of
assessing performance and use a multiple index for complete
assessment of efficiency in finances, assets management,
operational risks, and sustained growth ability.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in the country's history, they provide a
yearly index of SOE performance based on statistics of all SOEs to
set a different specific index for various industries. By
comparing each individual SOE with these standards, differences in
the actual efforts of various enterprises can be shown to improve
performance.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Finance official said that, in the past, various
government departments used different ways to assess the
performance of SOEs, a practice that put an excessive burden on
the enterprises and still failed to reflect the true state of
their performance.
</P>
<P>
The new standards reform the old system in management and
supervisory methods and in assessing performance, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation Along Kenyan-Somali Border Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The security situation along the
common border between Somalia and Kenya is returning to normal
Friday after serious tension rose Thursday following the looting
by Somali militiamen of Kenyan army equipment across the border.
</P>
<P>
According to the VHF radio reports near the border, the Somali
villagers and nomads living in the border areas have been
terrified by the Kenyan air force angered by the Somali militiamen
who crossed the border to disarm some of Kenyan soldiers
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan helicopter gun-ships and fighter jets flew over the
border between Kenya and Somalia all day Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The latest reports from the region indicated that the tension
has been defused after Colonel Barreh Hiraleh from the Somali
National Front (SNF) faction turned the two looted lorries to
General Agoi (one name), commander of the Kenyan military forces
in the northeastern region, and other officials at Ammuma village
where looting took place two days ago.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Hiraleh said that his men are working hard to return
other equipment stolen from the Kenyan forces including some
ammunition and uniforms, pledging that the rest of the equipment
would be turned over later Friday.
</P>
<P>
The colonel and other Somali officials have arrived from the
southern port town of Kismayu to tackle the situation at the
border.
</P>
<P>
The Somali militiamen who crossed the border have reportedly
been chasing their opponent militiamen supporting General Mohamed
Saed Hirsi Morgan who lost the town of Kismayu to the Jubba Valley
alliance last month.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, serious efforts have been made by
General Omar Hajji Masalleh, chairman of the SNF faction, who is
currently in Kenyan capital Nairobi to arrange the safe return of
the lorries and other military equipment looted by his men.
</P>
<P>
In a written message General Masalleh has apologized to the
Kenyan government and pledged that the equipment would be returned
by Friday, and this has shown some positive results.
</P>
<P>
Despite the efforts from the Somali side, still Kenya showed
concern over the situation along the border, since the Kenyan
government reportedly closed the border with Somali Friday
</P>
<P>
Here in Mogadishu, the politicians are also expressing concern
over the new possibility of Kenyan soldiers crossing into Somalia
after the factional and clannish war between the Somalis had
spilled over to their best neighbor of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Professor Issa Mohamed Siad, a top aid of faction leader
Hussein Mohamed Aidid here in Mogadishu has forwarded his apology
to Kenya for what has happened at the border Somalia shares with
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Kenya has all the time been the best friend of Somalia by
accommodating our refugees and assisting them," he said. "We're
working together to return all the equipment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
