<HEADLINE> Sampras, Agassi Through into Semi-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi were
on match away from an all-America final showdown in the Wimbledon
Open men's singles as both advanced into the semi-finals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
No. 1 seeded Sampras survived from one-set down against
Australian Mark Philippoussis, who retired with a knee injury in
the second set.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, who was seeking for a Wibledon and French Opens double,
crashed Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten 6-3, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Other two semis are Britain's Tim Henman, who snapped injured
Cedric Pioline of France 6-4, 6-2, 4-6, 6-3, and Patrick Rafter of
Australia, who also took advantage of injury to his opponent,
defeating Todd Martin of the United States 6-3, 6-7 (7-5), 7-6 (7-
5), 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who has five titles in his pocket, will meet Henman,
whom he beaten in last year's final, while Agassi face Rafter.
</P>
<P>
In women's play, 18-year-old American Alexandra Stevenson
stopped storming Jelena Dokic in a rain-suspended match, 6-3, 1-6,
6-3.
</P>
<P>
Stevenson, who is playing her first tournament as a pro, became
the first qualifier in Wimbledon history to reach the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
She will play seven-time champion Steffi Graf of Germany in
Saturday's semis, while American Lindsay Davenport faces Mirjana
Lucic of Croatia, who beat Nathalie Tauziat, 4-6, 6-4, 7-5.
</P>
</TEXT>
