<HEADLINE> Thai Govt Can Do Without SAP: Interior Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Sanan Kachornprasart, Thailand's
Interior Minister in charge of election affairs, said Friday that
the government can do without the outgoing Social Action Party
(SAP).
</P>
<P>
Newly-elected SAP leader Suvit Khunkitti announced earlier
Friday that his party has decided to quit the Thai coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Sanan said that since SAP could not solve its internal problems
and manage to stay in the coalition, what the government could do
was let it be.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Suvit said he believed that SAP's withdrawal will
not affect the stability of the coalition government, which
originally enjoyed a 257 majority in the 393-seat lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
SAP's decision to quit was made at a SAP congress earlier in
the day, which was to elect a new party leader and an executive
committee.
</P>
<P>
Suvit, former party leader who quit the post amid an internal
row over cabinet seats allocation under the party's portfolio, was
re-elected as party leader.
</P>
<P>
And a 37-member executive committee, including Suvit himself,
was also elected at the party congress.
</P>
<P>
SAP holds 20 seats in the House of Representatives. It was one
of the seven partners within the current Chuan Leekpai government,
led by the Democrat Party.
</P>
<P>
SAP used to control five cabinet posts in the government. But
all of its ministers resigned before the party congress.
</P>
<P>
SAP's decision to quit was well anticipated by local political
analysts after a month-long struggle within the party over cabinet
seats pending a government reshuffle this month.
</P>
<P>
Rebel factions, led by party advisor Rakkiat Sukthana and party
secretary-general Somsak Thepsuthin, had demanded Suvit give up
his science minister post and keep only the deputy premiership.
But Suvit refused to give in to the demand even after the rebels,
who controlled nine of the party's 20 seats in the lower house,
threatened to withdraw their support for the government.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he fought back by resigning as party leader, forcing
the party to choose a new leader, a battle he had confidence to
win.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said SAP's withdrawal showed that Suvit, though
successfully re-elected, failed to quell the differences within
his party.
</P>
<P>
With SAP's decision to quit the coalition, the government is
expected to conduct a reshuffle in the following two or three
days.
</P>
<P>
A well-informed source said that four of the five cabinet posts
made vacant by SAP's withdrawal will be shared by the three
largest parties in the coalition -- the Democrat, Chart Pattana
Party and Chart Thai Party.
</P>
<P>
He said Chart Pattana, the second largest party in the
coalition which holds 51 seats in the lower house, will get the
lion's share of two posts. The Democrat, holding 123 seats, and
Chart Thai Party, 39 seats, will each bag one in their respective
portfolios. One job is still at stake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
