<HEADLINE> China's "Silicon Valley" Looking for Talented People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- China's prestigious Qinghua
University reached an agreement today with Beijing's Haidian High-
Tech Development Zone to train engineers for the Zhongguancun area.
</P>
<P>
Zhongguancun in northwestern Beijing, which is known as China's
"silicon valley", is home to nearly 5,000 private high-tech
businesses and dozens of academies and research institutes like
those at Beijing and Qinghua universities and the Chinese Academy
of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,100 of the world's top computer companies, like IBM,
Microsoft, Compaq, Hewlett Packard, and Mitsubishi, have ventures
in the area.
</P>
<P>
According to Qinghua sources, the university has promised to
have 100 people graduate with a master degree in engineering every
year for the Zhongguancun area to help further development there.
</P>
<P>
In return, the university will be given help in establishing
more high-tech businesses for commercializing research
achievements in the area, and funds will be available to back the
development of such high-tech enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
