<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Improving, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Coordinating Minister
for Economy, Finance and Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita Friday
expressed the government's optimism about the country's economic
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar said the optimism stems from the improving
macroeconomic indicators which were "sustainable."
</P>
<P>
"I believe that current economic growth is sustainable. If
political stability is maintained, I am optimistic that
Indonesia's economic performance will be better than the 0.13
percent estimate made by the Central Bureau of Statistics,"
Ginandjar told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The government has predicted that economic growth would be
between zero to two percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar said the sustainable growth showed the success of the
country's economic recovery program with the support of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The improving economic condition is marked by positive growth,
the strengthening exchange rate of the rupiah, decreasing
inflation rates, and declining bank interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, which was around 8,500 rupiah against the U.S.
dollar before the June 7 poll, has risen past 7,000 rupiah last
week, and is now trading around 6,700 rupiah against the
greenback.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia posted a deflation of 0.18 percent in March, 0.68
percent in April, 0.28 percent in May and 0.34 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said his country's export has notched up an
increasing trend, while the economy has begun to recover.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the rupiah's exchange rate against the U.S.
dollar, Ginandjar maintained that 6,000 rupiah to the dollar would
still be conducive to the growth of the Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
"Six thousand rupiah to the dollar will be okay, because it is
still favorable to the repayment of foreign debts and the control
of inflation, while still unproblematic to the export drive," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
