<HEADLINE> Russia, France Discuss Ties After Balkan Air War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
on Friday that both Russia and France need to learn from the
lessons of the Kosovo crisis "for further cooperation in both
bilateral and international affairs."
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin at the Kremlin, Yeltsin noted that Moscow's ties with Paris
were strained by "the military action of NATO countries in the
Balkans, in which France took part," according to Sergei Prikhodko,
Yeltsin's deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yeltsin said the Kosovo crisis has also been
reflected in "the mutual understanding of Russia and France
regarding the need to expand privileged cooperation" between the
two countries, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, for his part, said "France attaches and will continue
to attach great significance to the U.N. role in the settlement of
conflicts similar to those in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"The Kosovo precedent must not become a rule," Prikhodko
quoted Jospin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders "expressed confidence that cooperation between
the military peacekeepers from the two countries in Kosovo would
be exemplary, or example-setting in character," Prikhodko said.
</P>
<P>
Besides Kosovo, Yeltsin and Jospin also discussed bilateral
trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, who arrived here Thursday on a two-day official visit,
will also meet with his Russian counterpart, Sergei Stepashin, for
the fifth meeting of the French-Russian inter-governmental
commission on economic and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Jospin's entourage includes Minister of Economics, Industry
and Finance Dominique Strauss-Kahn, Minister of Agriculture and
the Fishing Industry Jean Glavany and a group of businessmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
