<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Vows to Protect Working Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government vowed on
Friday to protect the country's more than 3.7 million working
children from harm by strictly enforcing the laws prohibiting the
employment of minors in hazardous working conditions.
</P>
<P>
Felicisimo Joson, undersecretary of the Department of Labor and
Employment (DOLE), told a meeting that many working children are
either exposed to hazardous working conditions or too long hours
of work.
</P>
<P>
Joson stressed that the law prohibits the employment of
children below 15 years old in public or private undertakings,
saying the DOLE was mandated to promulgate the rules for the
effective enforcement of labor law.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the law, a "go" signal can be given when
the child would work directly under the sole responsibility of his
or her parents or legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
Also, Filipino children could work in public entertainment
areas such as cinema, theater, radio or television production
where their employment or participation "is essential."
</P>
<P>
But Joson said that while the law provides for exceptions, it
nevertheless mandates the employer to ensure the protection,
health, safety, morals, and normal development of the child.
</P>
<P>
It likewise obligates the employer to institute measures to
prevent the child's exploitation or discrimination, he added.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, he said, the employer should first secure a
work permit before engaging the services of the child to ensure
his or her protection against unscrupulous or exploitative
employers.
</P>
<P>
Joson admitted that the task of safeguarding the children's
right is no easy job and called for the support of the whole
society in the effective and full implementation of the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Rebukes Clinton's Remarks Over Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- In his first exchange of harsh
words with Israel's most important ally, Prime Minister-elect Ehud
Barak criticized U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday for his
remarks supporting the return of hundreds of thousands of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued earlier in the day, Barak described as
"unacceptable" Clinton's stance on the refugees' right of return.
</P>
<P>
"It's apparently a misunderstanding, and it would have been
appropriate for the (U.S.) administration to clarify and correct
it," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference with visiting Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak in Washington Thursday, Clinton said the Palestinian
refugees should be free to live "wherever they like."
</P>
<P>
While responding to a question on whether he would work to
ensure the return of Palestinian refugees, Clinton said, however,
as a practical matter, whether the refugees go home depends on,
among other things, how long they've been away and whether they
wish to return.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Palestinians were forced to flee
from their home when the Jewish state was proclaimed in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 3 million refugees and their descendants
are scattered in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip as well as
neighboring Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been opposed to the return of the refugees for fear
that it will cause a major impact on the character of the Jewish
state, which has a population of 6 million.
</P>
<P>
The future of the refugees, together with other thorny issues
in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict such as the fate of
Jerusalem, is supposed to be discussed in the final-status talks,
which has yet to be started.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who trounced the hard-line Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu in the May election, has pledged to reinvigorate the
stalled Middle East peace process in all tracks. He will present
to the parliament next week of a new government he has put
together through six weeks of grueling talks.
</P>
<P>
Washington and the Arab world have hailed "a new era of
peacemaking" since Barak secured a broad support for his policy
by forming a government with a 75-seat majority in the 120-member
parliament.
</P>
<P>
But observers said Barak, an ex-army chief, wanted to send
a message to Clinton and Israel's Arab neighbors that he will
be tough in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA), which has developed
warm relations with Washington in three years when Netanyahu was
in office, has welcomed Clinton's remarks on the refugees,
saying they are "encouraging."
</P>
<P>
But Ziad Abu Zayyad, a PNA cabinet member, cautioned that
while Clinton's remarks are very important, the Palestinians
understand that practically speaking, Israel will not accept a
massive return.
</P>
<P>
"We won't ask the Israelis to commit suicide, we won't
ask them to give up their state and turn it into a state
of an Arab majority...The problem must be resolved through
negotiations," he told Israel Radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Reserves Position Improved: C. Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The South African Reserve Bank
Friday reported further improvement in the reserves position of
the country.
</P>
<P>
The central bank of South Africa said its provisional gross
gold and foreign exchange reserves amounted to 35.1 billion rand
(5.85 billion U.S. dollars) on June 30 this year, 800 million rand
(133 million dollars) more than that at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
The use of foreign credit lines at the end of June amounted to
16 billion rand (2.67 billion dollars), compared to 16.4 billion
rand (2.73 billion dollars) on May 31.
</P>
<P>
The net open foreign currency position was 18.3 billion dollars
at the close of business on June 30, compared to 19.3 billion
dollars at the end of the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding oversold forward book of the bank was 21.5
billion dollars at close of business on June 30, compared to 22.2
billion dollars at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
The improvement has sparked renewed calls for domestic interest
rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
Bruce Teubes, economist with Standard Bank Investment
Corporation (Stanbic) said Friday: "The reserves data complete a
week which, with the exception of the PPI (producer price
inflation) data, has been extremely supportive of the case for
lower interest rates."
</P>
<P>
Teubes said that in dollar terms, gross reserves rose by about
300 million dollars during the month to 5.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"With virtually no change in the use of foreign credit lines,
net reserves also rose by 300 million dollars to stand at 3.2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The rand value of reserves did not reflect the same
proportional increase because of the stronger level of the
exchange rate at the end of June (one U.S. dollar equals to 6.03
rand) compared with the end of May (one dollar equals to 6.21
rand)," he added.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of the producer price inflation -- affected
negatively by higher oil prices -- the national economic data
released this week has all been good news.
</P>
<P>
The Quarterly Bulletin of the South African central bank showed
a 5.4 billion rand (900 million dollars) improvement in the
country's reserves in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The monthly released Thursday indicated a further build-up in
the country's reserves in April, meaning the balance of payments
remained in surplus. 
</P>
