<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Defense Committee Calls for Talks on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Defense Committee of
the Cabinet (DCC), meeting here on Friday, renewed the call for a
negotiated settlement of the current Kashmir crisis.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting chaired by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, the DCC
reiterated Pakistan's stand that all issues including the current
crisis should be resolved through negotiations in the spirit of
the Lahore Declaration signed by the prime ministers of Pakistan
and India in February.
</P>
<P>
The committee expressed the hope that India will realize the
"serious consequences of a wider conflict" and avoid this
"perilous course" in the interest of peace and stability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan does not want war, but if war is imposed, Pakistan is
fully capable of defending every inch of its territory," it said
in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, also attended by high-ranking cabinet ministers
and the chiefs of the three services the armed forces, is the
DCC's first since the eruption of serious conflicts along the Line
of Control (LoC) in Kashmir in early May.
</P>
<P>
The five-hour meeting reviewed the current Kashmir situation.
The committee was given detailed briefings by Chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee and Chairman of Army Staff General
Pervez Musharraf and Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
The DCC expressed the "satisfaction" that the defense forces
and the whole nation were prepared to deal with "any eventuality"
and to give an effective response to "any act of aggression."
</P>
<P>
The committee also expressed its regret that India had failed
to respond to the various positive initiatives of Pakistan to
de-escalate the situation leading to peaceful negotiations for
resolving the current crisis, according to the press release.
</P>
<P>
A detailed briefing on Sharif's recent visit to China was also
given to the committee, which appreciated the reiteration of
China's traditional friendship and support for Pakistan and its
deep interest in the maintenance of peace and stability in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The committee noted with satisfaction that the Chinese leaders
had endorsed Pakistan's stand for de-escalation of the LoC
situation, mutual respect by India and Pakistan for the sanctity
of the LoC and resumption of dialogue between them, said the press
release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
