<HEADLINE> Nebiolo Re-elected to FISU Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Primol Nebiolo was reelected
to the presidency of the Federation of the International Students
Union (FISU) for another term of four years here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the general assembly, the Italian who has been chairing the
organization since 1961, won his reelection by a small margin of
votes.
</P>
<P>
Nebiolo, also president of the International Federation of
Athletics, started his implication in the sport university
movement from the end of the Second World War as a student of the
University of Torino.
</P>
<P>
For Nebiolo, the Universiade which will celebrate its 50th
anniversary in Palma de Mallorca on July 10, has consolidated as
the more important sport event after the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Still with less sports than the Olympic Games, Nebiolo is still
proud of the 87 gold medals, 86 silver and 67 of bronze that
athletes in the previous 19 Universiade have conquered in the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
And for the Palma Universiade which will open tomorrow, there
are also some big names with the participation of swimmers Amanda
Beard and Anita Nall of the United States who won the Olympic
golds from the Atlanta and Barcelona respectively.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly has also studied the candidacies of 14
student associations that apply for the membership of the FISU,
which at the moment counts with 113 members.
</P>
<P>
FISU also ratified that Beijing will host the 21st Summer
Universiade and decided that the 2001 Winter Universiade will be
held in Zakopane of Poland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
