<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugee Camp Crowded in W. Tanzania: Red Cross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A Red Cross refugee camp in western
Tanzania is struggling to cope with thousands of people fleeing
conflicts from the Democratic of Republic of Congo and it is in
danger of being overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
The camp at Lugufu, 90 kilometers east of the Lake Tanganyika
port of Kogoma, is stretched beyond capacity for weeks with up to
2,000 refugees a day crossing the lake, according to the Regional
Delegation of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies.
</P>
<P>
"Close to 370,000 refugees are being helped in Tanzania before
the latest influx and all the region's camps are under pressure,"
the mission said in a press release issued here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We face a potentially explosive situation in Lugufu," said
Jane Buchan, acting head of the mission.
</P>
<P>
She explained that the Lugufu camp, run by the
federation-supported Tanzania Red Cross, is designed for maximum
40,000 refugees, but it has 55, 000.
</P>
<P>
However, an emergency operation is underway to prepare for
another 7,000 due to arrive in the coming week, she added.
</P>
<P>
Buchan said that the camp had run out of shelter materials and
some 18, 000 people are without cooking utensils.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that the mortality rate rose during May and June
and deaths among children under five are particularly worrying.
</P>
<P>
Within the next few days, she said, two or three new villages
must be constructed, two more health posts set up and more water
points provided in the camp.
</P>
<P>
Appealing for more funding for the camp, Buchan said that
serious consideration must be given to constructing a second camp
in Lugufu but all scenarios present an urgent need for funding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
