<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Stock Rebounds As Investors' Confidence Regains (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some investors note that the nose-diving stock on China's two
bourses in the past two days did not make sense.
</P>
<P>
The stock index in China's two bourses in Shanghai and Shenzhen
closed down sharply Thursday by over 7 percent with a total of 549
company stocks drifting down.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts attribute the drop to the sell-off by
institutional investors after they took big profits from the
upward trend in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Many investors and analysts say that they would not be
surprised to see a little correction after the stock rising by 50
percent over the past month. However, such an abrupt fall did not
make sense, especially when the investment climate is favorable.
</P>
<P>
China's first securities law went into effect on July 1, which
is generally expected to intensify the efforts to ensure a healthy
stock market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, CITIC Securities Co. Ltd. announced Thursday that
its registered capital has increased to 2.1 billion yuan (about
260 million U.S. dollars). On the same dayt, another two
investment funds worth 3 billion yuan each were issued.
