<HEADLINE> Thailand Announces 3.8 Billion Dollar Asset Auction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai authorities announced plans on
Friday to auction 3.8 billion U.S. dollars worth of loan
portfolios from failed finance firms.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank's Financial Sector Restructuring
Authority said in a statement that it had finalized plans to put
the loans on the block in a one-day sale on August 3.
</P>
<P>
The sale, announced exactly two years after the float of the
baht which triggered the Asian financial crisis, will be the
latest in a series of auctions that has so far netted more than
one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government last month hailed previous auctions of
assets from 56 finance firms, closed after the crisis, as a
success and a sign of a return of consumer confidence.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from the sales are being used to pay creditors of the
closed finance companies. 
</P>
