<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Try to Retrieve Looted Public Funds: VP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Vice-President Atiku
Abubakar said Thursday that the government will take efforts to
retrieve the looted public funds by former corrupt officials once
necessary facts have been secured.
</P>
<P>
When meeting a U.K. non-governmental delegation in capital
Abuja, Atiku urged the countries that may be affected to cooperate
with the government.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian newspaper Friday quoted the vice-president as
saying that his government would be ready to make such recoveries
on a negotiated basis.
</P>
<P>
Some European Union countries had earlier stated that Nigeria
must furnish concrete proofs before their investigation of the
suspected bank accounts could start.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted unspecified sources as saying that there are
about 55-billion-U.S.-dollar black money stashed in foreign
accounts.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting with the British delegation, Atiku regretted
that Nigeria did not benefit from the debt reduction recently
announced by the G-8 countries during their last meeting.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president noted that the economic situation of the
most populous African country was on the decline.
</P>
<P>
He said that if Nigeria's debt burden was not reduced by the
international community, it would get to a point where the
community would be invited to help in solving the problems of
poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
The new democratic dispensation, he complained, was already
being threatened by poverty which had been linked to the debt
burden.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has accumulated a foreign debt of about 32 billion
dollars, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
Atiku assured that his government is ready to improve the
fortunes of the west African country by reversing the trend in
conformity with the expectations of the international community.
</P>
<P>
Accountability and transparency were already in practice in
government dealings, the vice-president added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
