<HEADLINE> Nobel Laureate Lauds Obasanjo's efforts to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Nobel Laureate Prof. Wole
Soyinka has lauded the new civilian government's efforts to
stabilize the economy and probe the human rights abuses of past
military regimes, The Guardian paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
After paying a visit to President Olusegun Obasanjo Thursday,
the Nobel laureate said that by the Nigerian government's moves to
recover what has been stolen from the country and moves to recover
government property which had been looted are "highly commendable
steps."
</P>
<P>
Soyinka spoke of plans by his National Liberation Council of
Nigeria, an organization to send a memorandum to the rights abuse
probe panel established by the government.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the media already had "overwhelming evidence"
on human rights abuses perpetrated during the Sani Abacha
administration, Soyinka urged them to assist the panel in its
assignment.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the National Assembly, parliament of this west
African country, to take "a critical look at the constitution" so
as to achieve "the real structural meaning of democracy."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria had just emerged from a nightmare, he noted, pledging
that he would strive to play his role to enthrone true democracy
and to continue the "struggle to open and widen this aperture
toward democracy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
