<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.N. Committee of Blocking Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin
Ramadan has criticized the U.N. Sanctions Committee for impeding
the contracts Iraq signed under the oil-for-food deal, the Iraqi
News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
When meeting with visiting Executive Director of the
U.N. Program for Iraq Benon Sevan on Thursday evening, Ramadan put
the blame on the U.S. and British representatives with the
Sanctions Committee, or 661 Committee.
</P>
<P>
During the past five phases of the oil-for-food program, the
U.S. and British representatives with the 661 Committee had put
hundreds of contracts on hold, said the vice president.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that the contracts which were on hold covered
electricity, health, agriculture, education, foodstuff and medical
appliances.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal which has been in place since
December 1996, Iraq is allowed to export a limited amount of oil in
every six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its people.
</P>
<P>
The vice president said that due to the hegemony of the
U.S. representatives with the U.N. committee, the
U.N. Secretariat-General's role is very weak in implementing and
following up the Iraqi contracts.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Benon Sevan, who has visited some areas in Iraq,
said that he appreciated Iraq's cooperation with him and pledged
to exert utmost efforts to put the Iraqi contracts into effect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
