<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Gain More than 600 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks soared by 652.44
points on Friday, following the U.S. Federal Reserve's move to a
neutral stance on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index finished at 14,184.58 points, up 4.82
percent over Wednesday. The stock market was closed Thursday to
mark the second anniversary of the establishment of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The market turnover also increased dramatically to 14.364
billion HK dollars (about 1.841 billion U.S. dollars) from 12.042
billion HK dollars (1.544 billion U.S. dollars) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sub-indices of Finance, Utilities, Properties and Commerce &AMP;
Industry all registered gains between 4.2 percent and 5.68 percent.
</P>
<P>
Traders attributed the sharp increase to the news that the U.S.
Federal Reserve changed its policy stance to neutral from a
tightening directive on Wednesday and raised interest rates by 25
basis points.
</P>
<P>
China-related shares continued to increase with the Hang Seng
China Enterprises Index up 1.31 percent, and the Hang Seng China-
Affiliated Corporations Index up 3.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
The share prices rose 327.46 points, or 2.42 percent, to open
at 13,859.6 Friday. The prices continued to climb and finished the
morning session at 14,042.97.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index lost 233.35 points, or 1.7 percent, to
close at 13,532.14 Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
