<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Send 30 Observers for East Timor Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Thirty Pakistani nationals have
been selected as polling officers in the U.N.-sponsored elections
to be organized in East Timor next month, U.N. Volunteer (UNV)
Program Officer Rensje Van Neck said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news briefing, Neck added that Pakistan will
constitute one of the largest national contingents to assist in
the polling.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani volunteers have already participated in
U.N.-sponsored elections in Namibia (1989), Cambodia (1993) and
South Africa (1994).
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani volunteers to be sent to East Timor will be
deployed in the field and they will assist with voter
registration, maintain election records and select and supervise
local staff.
</P>
<P>
The first group of 20 has undergone training in Darwin,
Australia, with five of them already deployed in East Timor. The
remaining 15 will travel by plane to the island on Saturday. The
last group of 10 will leave Pakistan Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The popular consultation in East Timor, scheduled for August,
will decide on the territory's special autonomy or separation from
Indonesia. More than 400 UNVs, representing some 50 different
nationalities, will be deployed to facilitate the vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
