<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANA -- Lebanon's Albert Abila Group is planning to expand
its services for petroleum companies in Yemen during the coming
five years, the Arab daily Al Hayat reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Exploratory activities in Yemen were promising and 15
companies were already undertaking geophysical and seismic surveys
and were drilling test wells," said Assaf Maakaroum, Director of
the Group's branch in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The Group owns 39 percent of the shares of the Yemeni Supply
and Services Company and the rest 61 percent are owned by the
Yemeni Petroleum Investment Company under the Yemeni Ministry of
Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
The Albert Abila Group, which was founded about 50 years ago,
has some 32,000 employees in 40 countries. Its annual sales exceed
1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Exchange Program Office in the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) Thursday signed an agreement with the Mobile Oil
Qatar Inc., a subsidiary of the Mobile Corporation, for the
purchase of 300 million to 500 million cubic feet of natural gas
per day under the Dolphin project.
</P>
<P>
The accord has enabled the Dolphin project to receive the first
instalment of natural gas from the current available sources in
the UAE and the Omani Sultanate markets, local press reports said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Dolphin, the biggest energy project in the world, aims at
boosting economic development in the Gulf region. It is expected
to cost 8 to 10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The deficit in the unified government financial
account of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) reached 28.9 billion
dirhams (8 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998 as compared to 8.3
billion dirhams (2.5 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The overall deficit in 1998 accounted for 17 percent of the
gross domestic product (GDP) as against 5.1 percent in 1997 and 13
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UAE Central Bank has announced that the deficit
has been covered by government investment revenues, said the
bank's 1998 annual report.
</P>
<P>
The deficit rise was mainly attributed to the drop in oil
prices, UAE's adherence to its export quota as fixed by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) as well as
the hike in credit expenses and capital contributions.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Officials in charge of an international loan of 750
million U.S. dollars to fund a Qatari-U.S. petrochemicals joint
venture announced that the loan will be offered for contribution
next September in the regional and international markets.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary terms of the agreement were signed Wednesday in
London, entrusting 24 international banks with making arrangements
to cover 70 percent of the cost of the giant project for the
production of ethylene and polyethylene, the Arab daily Al Hayat
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari petrochemical complex will cost 1.97 billion
dollars, a joint venture by the Qatari General Petroleum
Authority and the U.S. Philips Petroleum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
