<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak to Import More Products in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has projected that it
would have an estimated total import bill of 9.8 billion U.S.
dollars in the 1999-2000 fiscal year (July 1-June 30).
</P>
<P>
Import of petroleum products is expected to increase by 422
million dollars to 1.8 billion dollars during the fiscal year
which began on July 1, official sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The import of petroleum products is estimated at 1.4 billion
dollars during the 1998-99 fiscal year as against the target of
1.49 billion dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tea import in the new fiscal year is projected at
247 million dollars, showing a nominal increase of 6.5 percent
over its import of 232 million dollars in 1998-99.
</P>
<P>
The projected import of wheat during the current fiscal year
shows a decline of 29 percent to 265 million dollars when compared
with an estimated import of 373 million dollars during the 1998-99
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The planned target of wheat import in 1998-99 was fixed at 249
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Edible oils import is projected at 767 million dollars, showing
a decline of 9.6 percent when compared with the estimated imports
of 848 million dollars during the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The import of fertilizers for the 1999-2000 fiscal year is
projected at 190 million dollars as against an estimated amount of
203 million dollars for 1998-99, recording a decline of 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
The import of all other items including textiles, agricultural
products, metals and others is estimated at 3.99 billion dollars
in the new fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has projected the trade deficit for
the new fiscal year at 800 million dollars, with exports targeted
at 9 billion dollars and imports worth 9.8 billion dollars,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to announce its annual trade policy
on July 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
