<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Action Party Quits Thai Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Social Action Party (SAP)
decided to quit the Thai coalition government, the SAP's
newly-elected leader Suvit Khunkitti announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Suvit said it is the decision of the SAP party congress which
was held here earlier Friday aiming to elect a new party leader
and an executive committee.
</P>
<P>
Suvit, a former party leader who quitted the post amid an
internal dispute over cabinet seats allocation under the party's
portfolio, was re-elected as party leader.
</P>
<P>
And a 37-member executive committee, including Suvit himself,
was also elected at the party congress.
</P>
<P>
The SAP holds 20 seats in the 393-strong House of
Representatives. It was one of the seven partners within the
current Chuan Leekpai government, led by the Democrat Party.
</P>
<P>
The SAP used to control five posts in the cabinet, but all its
ministers resigned before the party congress.
</P>
<P>
The decision of the SAP's quitting the government was well
anticipated by local political analysts after a month-long
struggle within the party over cabinet seats pending a government
reshuffle this month.
</P>
<P>
Rebel factions, led by party advisor Rakkiat Sukthana and party
Secretary-General Somsak Thepsuthin, had demanded that Suvit give
up his science minister post and keep only the deputy prime
ministership. But Suvit refused to give in to the demand even
after the rebels, who controlled nine of the party's 20 seats in
the lower house, threatened to withdraw their support for the
government.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he fought back by resigning as party leader, forcing
the party to hold a new executive committee to choose a new
leader.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the SAP's withdrawal showed that Suvit, though
successfully re-elected, failed to quell the differences within
his party.
</P>
<P>
With the SAP's decision to quit the coalition, the government
is expected to conduct a reshuffle in the next two to three days.
</P>
<P>
A well-informed source said four of the five cabinet posts made
vacant by the SAP's withdrawal will be shared by the three largest
parties in the coalition, namely the Democrat Party, Chart Pattana
Party and Chart Thai Party.
</P>
<P>
He said Chart Pattana, the second largest party in the
coalition which holds 51 seats in the lower house, will get the
lion's share of two posts. The Democrat, holding 123 seats, and
Chart Thai Party, 39 seats, will each bag one more post in their
respective portfolios. The last post is yet to be decided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
