<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Planet Named after Chinese Astronomer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A minor planet has been named after
Qu Qinyue, a Chinese astronomer, with the approval of the
International Minor Planet Center and the International Minor
Planet Nomenclature Committee.
</P>
<P>
Minor Planet No.3513 was discovered in October 1965 by the
Purple Mountain Observatory under the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS).
</P>
<P>
Qu is the fifth Chinese astronomer to have a minor planet named
after him. The other astronomers are Zhang Yuzhe, Zu Chongzhi,
Zhang Heng, and Guo Shoujing.
</P>
<P>
Qu, one of the first Chinese astronomers engaged in research of
high-energy astrophysics, is now a professor of astronomy with
the Nanjing University, an academician of the CAS, and honorary
chairman of the Chinese Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
Qu became an academician of the Italy-based Academy of Science
for the Third World in 1993.
</P>
<P>
According to international convention, those who discover minor
planets and have confirmation from the International Minor Planet
Center have the right to name them.
</P>
<P>
The observatory in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province, has discovered 34 minor planets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
