<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imports Up But Exports Down in Central China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- In the first five months of this
year imports in central China's Henan Province reached 252 million
U.S. dollars, 20.1 percent up over the corresponding period last
year, while exports reached 409 million U.S. dollars, 13.3 percent
down.
</P>
<P>
Customs officials say that the main reason has been the adverse
impact of the Asian financial crisis, which led to 10 percent less
exports to the area. And the decrease in the exports of processing
industries has been the most noticeable, at 42.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The main causes for the increase of imports are: firstly, more
input in infrastructure construction which has encouraged domestic
demand which has accelerated imports in transportation, energy,
and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the reduction of the import tax rate has encouraged
state-owned enterprises to upgrade their technology with the use
of advanced equipment in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
China, as a whole, is to encourage imports by reducing the
average tariff rates from 17 to 15 percent next year, and that by
2005 they will be just 10 percent. And it plans to import a total
1,500 billion U.S. dollars of technology, equipment and products
within the next seven years, according to Sun Zhenyu, vice-
minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
He also said that the central government will encourage the
development of agriculture, hi-tech industries, infrastructure
construction, the environmental sector, and export-oriented
industries, in particular in central and western parts of the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
