<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surplus Higher Than Expected in New Zealand Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The full-year surplus of the New
Zealand government is likely to be higher than the 2.2 billion NZ
dollars (1.188 billion U.S. dollars) forecast in the budget, the
New Zealand Treasury said.
</P>
<P>
The government's financial statements for the 11 months to May
31, which was released Friday by the treasury, show the government
in surplus by 3.018 billion NZ dollars (1.63 billion U.S.
dollars) compared with a forecast 2.587 billion NZ dollars (1.397
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The treasury said the 431 million NZ dollar improvement on
11-month projections was due to higher-than-expected tax revenue,
a fall in expenses and better-than-anticipated net surpluses from
state-owned enterprises and other sources.
</P>
<P>
"The full year operation balance is likely to be somewhat
higher than the 2.2 billion NZ dollars forecast in the budget,"
the treasury said. But it noted that year-end adjustments would
also affect the full-year balance.
</P>
<P>
According to the treasury, the government's net worth was 422
million NZ dollars higher than forecast at 13.2 billion NZ dollars
while net debt was 587 million NZ dollars lower than expected at
21.556 billion NZ dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
