<HEADLINE> Lebanese Civilian Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese man was wounded in an
Israeli air raid on south Lebanon overnight, the Voice of People
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Ali Roumieh sustained injury when a missile fired by Israeli
warplanes hit his village of Kfarouman on the edge of the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
After the blast, Roumieh was rushed to a hospital in nearby
Nabatieh for treatment, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first casualty caused in the conflicts between
Israeli troops and Lebanese guerrillas since Israeli launched
the massive air strike on Lebanon last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Eight Lebanese were killed, 64 others wounded and the
country's infrastructure was ravaged in the attack, the biggest
since the Israeli 1996 "Grapes of Wrapth" operation on the country
which killed more than 200 people, most being civilians.
</P>
<P>
Isarel defended its attack as a retaliation for the
cross-border raid by Hezbollah which killed two Israelis while
the Iraian-backed group said it fired Katyusha rockets into
northern Israel to avenge the wounding of six Lebanese by Israeli
shelling on south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by
Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli occupation troops
and its proxy South Lebanon Army out of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
