<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Wooden Buddha Makes Guinness Book of Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A wooden, gold painted
Buddhist figure with a thousand eyes and hands in Chengde, north
China's Hebei Province, has recently been included in the Guinness
Book of Records as the tallest statue of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
The figure, which was carved in 1755, is made of 120 cubic
meters of wood, enough to build a four story house. The Central
Research Institute for Relics Protection and the Prospecting and
Designing Institute under the Ministry of Construction measured
its exact height as 27.21 meters, using the most advanced remote
measuring utilities.
</P>
<P>
The Guinness Book of Records headquarters confirmed it as the
tallest wooden Buddhist statue in the world after a thorough
examination.
</P>
<P>
A stone carving featuring wide-eyed devils' heads in Fendu,
southwest China's Sichuan Province, was listed in the Guinness
Book of Records in 1997 as the world's largest stone carving at
138 meters high and 217 meters wide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
