<HEADLINE> Southern African States to Reach Free Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South African Trade and
Industry Minister Alec Erwin has said southern African states were
close to clinching a long-awaited free trade pact expected to set
the stage for their economic integration, the Citizen newspaper
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Thursday that he had enough negotiating
experience to know that the country were probably closest to an
agreement when the noise between the parties is at full steam.
</P>
<P>
"The noise that we now hear, the intense arguments and debates
in my view mean we're getting closer and closer to an agreement,"
he said in apparent reference to mounting calls from South
Africa's neighbors to conclude preferential trade deals.
</P>
<P>
Erwin did not say exactly when he expected a regional pact to
be wrapped up, but he said early this year that an agreement
should be in the bag by July.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, among other southern African states, has been
strongly advocating for a free trade pact. The country, which has
a large trade deficit with South Africa, accused Pretoria of
foot-dragging to conclude parallel talks to renew a bilateral
preferential trade deal which lapsed in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria says a bilateral pact with Zimbabwe -- South Africa's
largest trading partner in Africa -- was being held up by the
broader regional trade talks. 
</P>
