<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Recovery in Sight, Challenges Ahead for Thai Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Two years after the financial storm
hit Thailand and spread across Southeast Asia, the Thai economy
finally began to show signs of recovery.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, the central bank of Thailand announced that it
had given up its currency pegging system, triggering the collapse
of the baht and bringing down with it many other currencies in the
region, thus touching off a full-scale financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
With the aid of a 17.2-billion-U.S.-dollar rescue package of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and after the adoption of
numerous reform measures, the Thai economy is now considered by
many experts as on the way to recovery.
</P>
<P>
The Thai baht has been stabilized at 37 to the U.S. dollar for
months, compared with the lowest level of 56 to the dollar in
early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Local companies with foreign loans applauded the current
foreign exchange level, saying it will alleviate their debt
burden, although some experts argued that the baht is too high to
effectively promote the country's exports.
</P>
<P>
International reserves, which had nearly been depleted in the
baht defense battle with foreign speculators before the financial
crisis, returned to the pre-battle level of 31.1 billion dollars
as of June 11.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand recently announced that the country's
foreign debts have been reduced to 82.2 billion dollars from more
than 90 billion dollars when the crisis first broke out in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
Most importantly, debts of the private sector decreased sharply
from more than 80 percent of the total foreign debts to 58
percent.
</P>
<P>
After surging for a year to more than 10 percent at its peak in
June last year, inflation began to fall in the second half of 1998
and registered the first negative growth of 0.5 percent in May
1999.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's representative to Thailand Reza Moghadam said
recently that the policy Thailand has adopted and the measures
implemented are bearing fruit.
</P>
<P>
Thailand adopted an austerity policy following the IMF's
proposals, which featured tightened control of commercial banks'
lending and increased provision for their loans.
</P>
<P>
Four banks and 56 financial companies paid prices for their
relentless conduct before the crisis. The banks were nationalized
and the financial companies were closed at the end of 1997 by the
Chuan Leekpai government, which replaced the nine-month-old
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh government.
</P>
<P>
Realizing that banking reform is at the heart of the country's
economic recovery, the Thai government then introduced on August
14, 1998, a comprehensive financial reform package, helping banks
with their recapitalization.
</P>
<P>
And when the austerity policy brought the side-effect of
restricting domestic demand, the government then implemented a
130-billion-baht (3.5 billion dollars) stimulus package on March
30 this year. The package is aimed at cutting value-added tax and
personal income tax and spurring consumption with borrowed money
from the World Bank, Japan's Overseas Economic Cooperation Funds
and Japan's Export-Import Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 07:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resource Center to Help Tackle Y2K in Oman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A resource center will start
functioning within a week in Oman to help the country's private
sector tackle the computer millennium bug problem, known as Y2K, a
newspaper report said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The center will provide technical advice to private and
governmental organizations, create mass awareness to the problem
by distributing leaflets and holding seminars and workshops, the
Gulf News daily quoted Omani Minister of Commerce and Industry
Maqbool Bin Ali Bin Sultan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The center, to be run by the Omani Ministry of National
Economy, will also have a help-line desk in both English and
Arabic working around the clock to help private sector
organizations facing computer glitches, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Since many organizations were inter-dependent, a complete
coordination was imperative, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He explained that many developed countries had drawn up
contingency plans to fight the Y2K problem and Oman should not
lag behind.
</P>
<P>
"We are now focusing on computer system suppliers, especially
those who are engaged in supplying medical and telecommunication
equipments that directly affect the people's day-to-day life," the
minister told a gathering of computer and software experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Recovery in Sight, Challenges Ahead for Thai Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Thai government's measures have been warmly applauded by
the IMF and other economic bodies. However, great challenges are
still ahead for the vulnerable economy.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts here said the progress of Thai banks'
recapitalization is at a snail's pace despite the August 14
package, especially that of small banks which are facing a tough
time raising funds.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans (NPLs) were at a high level of 46 percent
of the total loans in commercial banks for the whole year of 1998,
which made the banks unwilling to make new loans to cash-strapped
enterprises, particularly those small and medium-sized ones.
</P>
<P>
The biggest challenge for Thailand now is the shrinking
exports, the so-called engine of economic growth in the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite a devalued currency, Thailand recorded a negative
growth in exports in 1998. The government targeted a 4-percent
growth to 56.6 billion dollars for this year. However, in the
first five months of 1999, exports on average dropped 0.3 percent
from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Bank of Thailand, the country's central bank,
lowered its 4-percent projection to 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
As the export engine is losing power, domestic consumption
became more important for economic recovery. However, the
inflation rate continued to fall since June last year, reflecting
a relatively weak public purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts here even predicted that the cloud of deflation
is looming large as reflected by the minus 0.5-percent growth of
the inflation rate in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the state budget was disbursed inefficiently, with
only 51.6 percent of the 825 billion baht (22.3 billion dollars)
having been disbursed in the first eight months of fiscal 1999,
which ends in September.
</P>
<P>
The government planned to spur the economy by expanding
government spending, allowed by a budget deficit accounting for 6
percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP). But
bureaucracy and the liquidity crunch faced by government project
contractors have cast a shadow over the real effect of the plan.
</P>
<P>
However, despite these hurdles, most economic experts in
Thailand are optimistic about the country's economic situation,
saying the government's projection of 1-percent GDP growth can be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
The National Economic and Social Development Board, a
government think-tank, and the central bank have estimated that
the Thai economy experienced a 0.9-percent growth in the first
quarter of this year, the first quarterly GDP growth since the
second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
They cited many positive signs appearing in recent months as
the reasons, among them NPLs, which slightly dropped in April to
42.06 percent of the total loans from 42.31 percent a month
earlier.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's Moghadam also said that as bad debts are dealt with,
restructuring progresses, the economy picks up and interest rates
go lower, the NPLs should be on a downward trend.
</P>
<P>
He also said the deflation fear was flawed, saying deflation
occurs when prices fall and output declines concurrently, which is
not the case in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the minus 0.5 percent inflation rate in May to
the cut in the VAT tax, which is part of the March 30 stimulus
package.
</P>
<P>
Also, exports in April and May recorded a growth of 4.7 percent
and 8.6 percent respectively after declines in the first three
months in 1999.
</P>
<P>
With good news from the region and the world, especially news
of a 1.9-percent GDP growth in Japan in the first quarter this
year, Thai exports are expected to have a better performance and
may even achieve the 4-percent growth target.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda once said Thailand would
continue borrowing from the IMF only if it is necessary.
</P>
<P>
After drawing 14.1 billion dollars from the 17.2-billion-dollar
multilateral package, the day for Thailand to stand on its own
feet is clearly at sight, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
