<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa in Midst of AIDS Epidemic, Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua)-- South Africa is in the midst of
an explosive AIDS epidemic which has increased 30-fold since 1990,
with no signs of stabilizing, local researchers have warned.
</P>
<P>
HIV rates have soared from 0.7 percent in 1990 to 22.8 percent
last year, with an estimated 3.6 million South Africans now
infected.
</P>
<P>
Findings by Quarraisha Abdool Kaarim and Professor Salum Abdool
Karim, both of the Medical Research Council's (MRC) Center for
Epidemiological Research in Southern Africa, were published in
this week's edition of the UK-based Journal of
Sexually-Transmitted Infections.
</P>
<P>
They said that while the seriousness of the HIV epidemic was
widely acknowledged, what was now becoming apparent was the
unprecedented escalation of the disease.
</P>
<P>
They confirmed earlier research that the disease was being
fuelled by migration, new infections in young women and high
levels of other sexually- transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
"The epidemic is spreading most rapidly in young South African
women who had HIV infection rates previously seen only in
high-risk sex worker populations," said Karim.
</P>
<P>
In just three years, HIV prevalence leapt from about seven
percent in 1992 to 21 percent in 1995 in the 20-to 24-year-old age
group, with about one in five young mothers attending ante-natal
clinics now infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
The researchers attributed this to the fact that older men were
seeking out younger women for relationships in the hope that this
would free them of infections, and the fact that a woman's risk of
infection was substantially higher if her partner was a migrant
worker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Epidemic Costs Kenya Dearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The AIDS epidemic has cost the
Kenyan government about 40 billion shillings (some 556 million
U.S. dollars) in the past 15 years, according to Kenya's National
AIDS Control Program.
</P>
<P>
"About 80 percent of deaths reported annually in government
departments are attributed to AIDS," Tom Okeyo, Project
Coordinator of the National AIDS Control Program, said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times newspaper Friday quoted Okeyo as saying that
close to 700,000 Kenyans have died of AIDS, which means an average
of 130 deaths per day.
</P>
<P>
The development gains of the 20th century will have been eroded
by the epidemic, Okeyo warned at a seminar on work ethnics
improvement.
</P>
<P>
"People are chained by cultural beliefs and practices that
approve multiple sex partners, which is one of the root causes for
the rapid spread of the epidemic in Kenya," said Okeyo.
</P>
<P>
The program coordinator also said that ignorance was no longer
the issue, urging people to talk about AIDS at all levels and show
compassion for 1.9 million Kenyans already infected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
