<HEADLINE> Kenyan Banks Increase Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Two commercial banks in Kenya have
increased their base lending rates in response to the recent rise
of treasury bill (TB) rate.
</P>
<P>
Commercial Bank of Africa and Standard Chartered Bank Thursday
announced the increases in their lending rates, from 16 percent to
18 percent and 15 percent to 16 percent respectively, as the
91-day TB rate rose to 13.4 percent from 12.26 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
Local financial analysts predicted that more banks will follow
suit soon which makes it hard for investors to borrow, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Base lending rates in the country started falling last December
after TB rates dropped drastically. In early June this year, the
Kenyan currency shilling weakened by 15 percent against the U.S.
dollar, causing panic in the economy of the east African country.
</P>
<P>
However, yield on TB went up by 44 percent two weeks ago, a
fact meant to attract foreign currency in a bid to help the
falling shilling.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the average commercial banks' base lending rate was
19 percent with the lowest rate at 15 percent from Standard
Chartered Bank and Barclays Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
