<HEADLINE> Philippines' Export Income Up 12.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines on Friday put its
export receipts from January through May at 12.942 billion U.S.
dollars, 12.4 percent up from the 11.515 billion dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
For May 1999, the total receipts went up by 13.6 percent to
2.744 billion dollars from 2.346 billion dollars a year ago, said
a report from the National Statistics Office.
</P>
<P>
Receipts from electronics and components, still the top dollar
earner with a 55.1-percent share, increased in the month by 38
percent to 1.513 billion dollars from 1.096 billion dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Articles of apparel and clothing accessories ranked second and
their sales amounted to 209 million dollars, 3 percent up over
202.9 million dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Input/output/peripheral units, emerging as the third, grossed
164.51 million dollars, which was 5.8 percent higher than the
155.42 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured goods, led by electronic equipment and parts,
posted a 22.3-percent increase as export sales reached 2.483
billion dollars from 2.03 billion dollars a year earlier. This
major export accounted for 90.5 percent of the total receipt.
</P>
<P>
Due to the drop in coconut products, the export value of
agriculture-based products totaled 129.41 million dollars,
declining from 171.13 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of goods included in special transactions, which
accounted for 3 percent of the total revenue, fell by 46.8 percent
to 81.03 million dollars from 152.19 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the Philippines' export to the United States, Japan,
the Netherlands and other seven top export markets amounted to
2.431 billion dollars or 88.6 percent of aggregate export
earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
