<HEADLINE> Israeli Consortium Buys Bulgaria's National Carrier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli consortium has bought
75 percent of Bulgaria's national carrier Balkan Air for 150,000
U.S. dollars and pledged to invest another 100 million dollars in
the troubled airline over the next five years, local media
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under a purchase agreement, the consortium consisting of Arkia
and the Ze'evi Group will assume responsibility for Balkan Air's
operations from mid-July, the Haaretz daily said.
</P>
<P>
Balkan Air is on the list of unprofitable Bulgarian companies
that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) is pressing the
government to close down by the end of June, another daily the
Jerusalem Post said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli investors, which beat bids from the Russian
Aviation Consortium and Ulrich Benteler of Germany, also agreed
to cover 111 million dollars of the airline's debts, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The new owners planned to expand the airlines' cargo activity
and its network of international, regional and local passenger
flights, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Arkia operates a charter airline in Israel and the Ze'evi
Group is involved in oil refining, civil engineering, real estate
and communications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Changes Rules to Back Technopreneurship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government Friday
announced the first set of changes in the existing rules and
regulations with a view to bringing about a conducive environment
for technopreneurial development.
</P>
<P>
Teo Ming Kian, chairman of the Technopreneurship 21 Executive
Committee formed by the government months ago, told a press
conference that the changes include revision of the bankruptcy
law, the exercise of revised employee stock option, new
technopreneur investment incentive scheme, new technopreneur home
office scheme, changes in government procurement policy and
changes in work pass and long-term visitors pass policies.
</P>
<P>
Teo said that with the changes to bankruptcy procedures and
laws, debt settlement without resort to bankruptcy allows debtors
to avoid the cost, stigma and inconvenience of bankruptcy and
gives creditors greater prospects for debt recovery.
</P>
<P>
Teo also said the government will allow capital losses incurred
by investors on their investment in technopreneurial start-ups to
be tax deductible if subject to qualifying criteria under a new
technopreneur investment incentive scheme.
</P>
<P>
The government has also decided to allow tax liability from
employee share options (ESOP) to be deferred for up to five years,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Teo affirmed that the government has agreed to let
technopreneurs use Housing Development Board flats, which used to
be restricted for residential use, and residential properties as
registered home offices.
</P>
<P>
On risk acceptance and management for government procurement,
Teo said the government has allowed technopreneurial start-up
companies to participate in certain public projects and government
bids and build and enhance their credibility.
</P>
<P>
On employment passes which now are mostly issued to foreigners
who have found employment in Singapore, Teo said long-term Social
Visits Passes and work passes will be issued to foreign talent and
technopreneurs to give them time to stay in Singapore and study
the opportunities to start their companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
