<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines May Import 500,000 Tons of Rice in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will import 300,000
to 500,000 tons of rice next year even though the weather
condition in the second half of 1999 is good for the country's
grain production, an official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
National Food Authority (NFA) administrator Gregorio Tan told
reporters here that the volume may be brought in either by the
government or the private sector by the first semester of 2000 to
ensure sufficient rice supply next year.
</P>
<P>
Tan said the country may have to import that amount even
without the expected rice shortages and projected sufficient
rainfall in the next six months because its rice stocks are not
enough for next year.
</P>
<P>
NFA administrator Edno Joson said the 1.2-million-ton rice
stocks as of the end of June this year may be only enough for the
next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
But the country will not import rice during the remaining
months of 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government already imported 991,000 tons of rice from
September 1998 to May 1999 due to food shortages caused by the
severe drought last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
