<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hot Weather to Continue in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Unusually hot weather, which has
had most of north China in its grip for a week will continue for
at least another three or four days, according to the Central
Meteorology Station (CMS).
</P>
<P>
It's the eighth consecutive day that Beijing has suffered
temperatures soaring constantly above 35 degrees centigrade, which
hasn't happened in half a century. Tianjin has also endured
similar high temperatures for several successive days.
</P>
<P>
Li Yanxiang, a research fellow with the CMS, attributed the
sweltering hot weather to a ridge of high pressure which has
dominated the area and predicted that it will extend southward in
the next few days.
</P>
<P>
However, Li says that the temperature in northeast parts of
Hebei province, Beijing and Tianjin municipalities will drop a
little after July 5, but that Shandong and Henan provinces will
continue to suffer in the heatwave.
</P>
<P>
Continuous high temperatures have led to a boom in sales of
heatstroke preventing products, such as ice creams, electric fans
and air conditioners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
