<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3rd Contingent of U.N. Civilian Police in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- At least 31 personnel forming the
third contingent of the U.N. Civilian Police under the U.N.
Mission on East Timor (UNAMET), arrived in Dili, capital of East
Timor, from Darwin, Australia, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Antara News Agency quoted UNAMET spokesman Ueki Yasuhiro as
saying the contingent includes 10 persons from the United States,
17 from Australia and four from Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The police members were also accompanied by six officials from
Australia and New Zealand, acting as military facilitators.
</P>
<P>
"So far the United States has not sent its civilian police, and
the presence of U.S. members in the contingent is a proof of
President Bill Clinton's attention to the direct ballot in East
Timor," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
With the third contingent, the number of U.N. civilian
policemen now has reached 104, while the total number of UNAMET
staff members and volunteers has reached 365.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5,
the United Nations will send civilian police advisers from several
countries to assist Indonesian police maintain law and order. A
key function will be to disarm rival factions that are either for
or against the territory's independence.
</P>
<P>
All the U.N. poll officers have been tasked to help Indonesian
policemen during the August direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The August ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations, which still considers Portugal as the administering power
of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
