<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Makes Progress in Y2K Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government services have
substantially increased its Y2K progress rate from 61 percent in
April to 72 percent in May, according to an official report
released here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report by the Presidential Commission on Y2K Compliance
said the increased progress rating, which was just 45 percent in
March, could be attributed to the commission's "call to action" to
various government agencies during consultations and seminars
conducted in the past months.
</P>
<P>
Another factor for the progress, it said, is the concerted
efforts by government agencies to be Y2K ready in anticipation of
the enactment of the Y2K bill, which President Joseph Estrada
signed into law on June 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K law mandates all government and private agencies to be
Y2K ready and allows government agencies to realign their funds
for Y2k projects.
</P>
<P>
Section 12 of the law allows for the filing of administrative,
criminal and civil charges against non-compliance in government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Government services are one of the seven mission-critical
sectors being monitored by the commission for Y2K compliance. The
other six sectors are finance, manufacturing, utilities, health
care, transportation and telecommunication.
</P>
<P>
The government sector includes the Departments of Environment
and Natural Resources, Labor and Employment, Interior and Local
Governments, Foreign Affairs, Agriculture and Agrarian Reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
