<HEADLINE> Indonesian Muslim Groups Protest Pornography in Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government and law
enforcers are under growing pressure to take stern measures
against pornography in the media as Islamic and women's groups
staged street rallies in the capital over the last two days.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of woman Muslim students, grouped in Calls for Human
Peace (Seruni) and the Indonesian Muslim Student Action Union
(KAMMI), Thursday staged a rally in front of the National Police
Headquarters in South Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The students, attired in Muslim apparel, unfurled banners and
repeatedly chanted "Women should respect their Aurat (private
parts)."
</P>
<P>
The protesters also pointed a finger at artists and photo
models who help to make sensual photos in tabloids and magazines.
</P>
<P>
"Our action is a moral call and a form of rejection of
vulgarity. This protest in part displays our concern about the
abusive freedom of the press," The Jakarta Post Friday quoted the
group's coordinator Azimah S. as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of members of a group called the Women's
Front of Generation Saviors (Bestari) Thursday burned copies of
the Popular magazine outside the office of Women Affairs Minister
Tuti Alawiyah in Central Jakarta to protest against pornography.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, at least 100 Muslim youths of the Action Front
for the Love of the Country staged a rally in front of the
National Police Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Pornography is another form of sexual harassment against women,
the group said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The National Police recently questioned witnesses regarding
issues of the Popular magazine, Pop tabloid, Obyektif tabloid and
the Liberty magazine, in relation to its investigation into
violations of the press' code of ethics.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta police Wednesday invited Muslim clerics to witness the
burning of pornographic VCDs and heroin.
</P>
<P>
Muslim opposition has intensified protest against the recent
explosion in the number of magazines. The protesters said pictures
of sexy women could destroy Indonesia's younger generation.
</P>
