<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloning Won't Help Giant Panda Conservation: Scientist (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A top Chinese anthropologist has
warned that cloning giant pandas will do little to help preserve
the precious species, insisting that the most effective
conservation is to let them evolve in the natural environment.
</P>
<P>
Professor Pan Wenshi of Beijing University, a world renowned
expert in giant pandas whose research has spanned two decades,
said that cloning is unable to guarantee either the gene quality
or the diversity of a species.
</P>
<P>
There are at present only an estimated 1,000 giant pandas
living in the wild and in zoos, and finding ways to save the rare
black and white bear which is threatened with extinction is the
aspiration of many scientists.
</P>
<P>
Professor Pan's comments follow the news that a Chinese
research team recently announced that they are just a step away
from the first cloned giant panda, having cultivated a giant panda
embryo by injecting a tiny coil of DNA taken from the nucleus of
one giant panda cell into a rabbit cell whose nucleus has been
removed.
</P>
<P>
If the embryo is put into the womb of a surrogate mother and
able to grow, the scientists assert, the first cloned panda will
greet mankind "in three to five years."
</P>
<P>
The latest achievement made by the team headed by Professor
Chen Dayuan of the Chinese Academy of Sciences is regarded as a
giant leap in the development of the cloning technology. However,
conservation scientists fear that both the public and the
government's faith in hi-tech development will divert their
attention and support from conservation of the species in the
natural environment, which has proved to be a time and money
consuming job.
</P>
<P>
"Cloning is feasible if the animal has lost its ability to
propagate," said Professor Pan. "But in fact, the giant panda's
reproductive ability is not as low as people imagine," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
