<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloning Won't Help Giant Panda Conservation: Scientist (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It is a common misconception that the giant panda's plight is
caused by its declining reproductive ability and the monotony of
its food," he pointed out. "On the contrary, the damage done by
mankind to its natural habitat is the main threat to its existence,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Fossils show that giant pandas spread in a vast area spanning
northern and southern China and some areas in Vietnam, Thailand,
the Laos and Myanmar. The drastic reduction of its population
occurred about 10,000 years ago, exactly when mankind started
agricultural cultivation.
</P>
<P>
Today, the species' habitats have been reduced to six mountain
systems in western China, according to the professor.
</P>
<P>
"Even so, giant pandas, whether living in the wilderness or in
zoos, have done well in breeding," he said.
</P>
<P>
The research center at Wolong Nature Reserve in the southwest
Sichuan province, a key panda habitat, has successfully bred two
to four cubs each year; while researchers stationed in Qinling,
over a nine-year observation period, found that the giant panda
population there grew by an annual 3.5 percent, higher than that
of the local human population.
</P>
<P>
Although Professor Pan voiced his support for development of
cloning technology using livestock and experiment animals for the
purpose of bringing humans better livestock and more effective
medicines he has his reservations about wild animals.
</P>
<P>
"Cloning them neither preserves their diversity nor the quality
of their genes and will be of no significance to their
conservation." he insisted.
</P>
<P>
The disadvantages of cloned animals have already be detected.
One estimate indicates that genetic abnormality occurs in less
than one out of 100 naturally bred embryos, 15 out of 100 tube-
bred ones, and half of those cloned.
</P>
<P>
"Why don't we devote our energy, time and money to helping
giant pandas reproduce healthier progeny in the natural way?"
asked Professor Pan.
</P>
<P>
He described a State Council's decree last year banning
lumbering in natural forests in the upper and middle reaches of
the Yangtze River, "good news" for the giant panda as it will help
protect 96 percent of the area where the animal lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Province Battles Early Summer Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- More than one million armymen and
civilians in east China's Zhejiang Province are battling floods,
which affected 7.9 million of the 43 million local people.
</P>
<P>
Well over 200,000 people have already been evacuated from flood-
stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang has experienced an unbroken spell of wet weather since
the advent of the rainy season during the first 10 days of June,
with total rainfall in some areas reaching as high as 806 mm, or
three times the level for a normal rainy season.
</P>
<P>
Continuing torrential rains sparked in heavy flooding in some
45 cities and counties in the northern part of the province, with
water levels in all major rivers and reservoirs in the areas
rising up to all-time highs. The water level in the Xin'anjiang
Reservoir located on the Qiantang River near Hangzhou, the
provincial capital, hit 108.2 meters on Thursday morning, the
highest mark since the reservoir was built in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters
estimates the flood water have destroyed 18,000 houses, damaged 3,
900 km of levees and inundated 478,000 hectares of farmland, with
direct losses approaching 5.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Vice Premier Wen Jiabao called Zhang Dejiang, secretary of the
Zhejiang Provincial Party Committee, on Thursday evening to
inquire about existing conditions. Wen urged the province to
continue all-out flood control and rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
Social stability prevails in flooded areas and local residents
have access to an adequate supply of goods, according to local
official source.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
