<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Current-Account Deficit Soars in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Israel's current-account deficit
soared 60 percent in the first quarter this year, up to 800
million U.S. dollars from 500 million dollars a year earlier,
according to official data made available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
On an annualized basis, the deficit for the whole year of 1999
is expected to be 2 billion dollars, compared with only 700
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The deficit rise is mainly attributed to an overall gap between
imported and exported goods and services, together with unilateral
payments, such as U.S. aid, which stands at 3 billion dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
Besides increased imports, mainly consumer product imports,
another cause for the deficit rise was an increase in foreign
debts, which rose by 1.1 billion dollars in the first quarter,
compared with a 600 million increase in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The figures published by the Central Bureau of Statistics also
showed that foreign investment fell 39 percent in the first
quarter to 1.1 billion dollars from 1.8 billion the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign financial investment posted a particularly steep drop,
totaling only 100 million dollars, compared with 1.6 billion for
the same period last year. The bulk of the decline in foreign
financial investment came from a sharp reduction of government
bond issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
