<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaitis to go to Polls on Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti voters will go to
polls on Saturday to elect a new four-year term National Assembly
(Parliament), which they hope will cooperate with the government
on important state issues.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Emir Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah dissolved the former
parliament on May 4, on the ground that it had misused
constitutional rights and violated ethics and morals of the Gulf
Arab state.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, a total of 112,882 males are
eligible for the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
A total of 288 registered candidates are contesting for 50
parliamentary seats at the 25 constituencies nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 500 people had originally registered for the race, but
over 200 of them pulled out as the deadline for withdrawals
expired on June 28.
</P>
<P>
Since there are no official political parties in Kuwait,
candidates are representing different government-tolerated
political groups. Some prominent and influential political
figures are even running as independents.
</P>
<P>
Tribal groups are expected to be dominant elements in
Saturday's elections as more than half of the constituencies
are considered to be tribal areas.
</P>
<P>
Candidates in the three main Islamic groups -- the Islamic
Popular Movement or Salaf, the Islamic Constitutional Movement
(ICM) and the Shia National Islamic Alliance (NIA) -- are
also believed to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
As Kuwait, like other oil rich Gulf nations, was heavily hit in
the past couple of years by the sagging oil prices in the global
market, domestic issues, especially the economic ones, have been
dominating the campaign platforms of most candidates.
</P>
<P>
The candidates called on the private sector to play a more
important role in the country's economy by employing more
national manpower, and promised to work on it if elected to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Some candidates also focused their speeches on the importance
of cooperation between the parliament and government.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation crisis triggered by policy differences between the
legislature and the executive authority has led to the
dissolution of the last parliament and the mass resignation of
the former cabinet in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Compared with economy, national security, the key issue in
the 1992 elections, has taken a backseat in the current
elections campaign speeches of most candidates.
</P>
<P>
Both candidates and voters said that they are feeling "more
secure at home and the defense agreements Kuwait signed with
foreign countries after the 1991 Gulf war are the main
reason for less preoccupation with national security in 1999."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
