<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Chief Reaffirms Neutrality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Minister Gen.
Wiranto Friday reaffirmed the Indonesian military's commitment to
neutrality during the upcoming general session of the People's
Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
Wiranto, who is also chief of the Indonesian Defense Forces,
said such neutrality does not mean that the forces will not use
their political rights and obligation.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at a parliamentary hearing with House
Commission I in charge of foreign and defense affairs, Wiranto
said that in securing the upcoming general session of the MPR, the
state police would play a big role.
</P>
<P>
It is in this context that the state police have intensified
their security operations in several parts of the city, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the Jakarta police command will deploy
81,000 personnel to secure the general session of the MPR. The
police force will also be aided by several platoons of the defense
forces, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Wiranto warned of possible mass rallies ahead of
the MPR general session which may create conflict between the
people and the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president.
</P>
<P>
The 700-strong MPR is made up of 200 government appointees and
the 500 members of the House of Representatives. The June 7
election will produce 462 legislators. A further 38 seats are
reserved for the military.
</P>
<P>
The military has repeatedly stressed that all the appointed
military legislators will vote for the best presidential candidate
of the country, whether he or she is nominated by major or minor
political parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
