<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish People Hail Rare Sunshine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Instead of the normally cloudy and
rainy weather of previous years, the Finnish people had a sunny
and bright June this year, the national meteorological agency said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The average temperature in Finland over the past month reached
about 18 degrees centigrade, the highest of this century for June,
said the Meteorological Office of Finland.
</P>
<P>
After mid-June, most parts of the Scandinavia country were
bathed in sunshine, with the temperature rising sharply, the
Meteorological Office said.
</P>
<P>
In the mid-east, the temperature ran around 25 and 28 degrees
centigrade for more than 10 days. The temperature in Helsinki and
the eastern city of Ilo Mantsi even rose above 30 degrees
centigrade.
</P>
<P>
The sunny weather was a pleasant surprise to the Finnish people,
who have to put up with the long and cold winter for about six
months every year.
</P>
<P>
This kind of weather is expected to continue, the
Meteorological Office said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
