<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Approves Plan to Buy 50 Second-hand Fighter Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Citing the economic crisis for buying the cheaper aircraft,
Chuan, also the defense minister of Thailand, said the aircraft
procurement would be subjected to further review by a top panel,
comprising military and defense officials in charge of military
budgetary allocation, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Thai Air Force Secretary AVM Prapas Chiemchawee was quoted as
saying that the 50 fighter jets would replace the OV-10
reconnaissance aircraft, scheduled to decommissioned in the next
three years. The jets would be deployed on aerial border patrol
operations.
</P>
<P>
The German government last February offered to sell its
decommissioned fighter, which had been out of deployment for two
years, as a government-to-government deal, the secretary added.
</P>
<P>
Based on the proposal, a fighter would cost one million baht
(27,000 U.S. dollars) but the actual price for each was to total
50 million baht (135,000 dollars), after additional costs for
pilot training and mechanical upgrading.
</P>
<P>
Each fighter had only 200 hours in the air despite its maximum
flight time of 15,000 hours. The under-used aircraft could be
deployed for another 20 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The alternative would cost the country about one billion baht
(27 million dollars) for each new fighter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
