<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Plays Down Russia-U.S. Warplanes Encounter, with correction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Thursday
that it was unconcerned about the incident in which two Russian
strategic bombers were reportedly intercepted by U.S. fighter jets
near Iceland.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said that the incident was
not "a militarily significant event."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. routinely protects the airspace of Iceland and I don'
t think there's anyone who believed that these two propeller
bombers posed a significant military threat," he said.
</P>
<P>
Two Russian strategic bombers flew within striking distance of
the United States last week as part of Moscow's largest military
exercise --West-99 -- since the end of the Cold War, The
Washington Post reported in its Thursday's edition.
</P>
<P>
The TU-95 Bear bombers were intercepted by four U.S. F-15
fighters and a P-3 patrol plane near Iceland early Friday morning
and escorted in a clockwise flight around the island, the
newspaper quoted U.S. officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen told a
Pentagon news conference Thursday, has multi-purposes though he
said "there's nothing that's surprised us" in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure it does have -- they have some multiple purposes,
perhaps domestic purposes, international purposes. They want to be
seen as remaining a force that one has to deal with. We deal with
them," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
However, The Washington Post said the U.S.-Russian warplane
encounter astounded U.S. officials and underlined recent Western
concerns about the military leadership in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
About 200 Russian peace-keepers surprisingly arrived in Kosovo
earlier than any NATO forces last month.
</P>
<P>
U.S. National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley said that
the bombers were flying in the international airspace as part of a
military exercise announced in advance by the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
"Russia routinely holds military exercises and we are not
particularly troubled by this. I don't think that there's any need
to over-dramatize this," Crowley added.
</P>
<P>
Moscow also downplayed the incident by denying any wrongdoing.
"Our planes did not violate any laws in that area," a Russian Air
Force spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen is expected to visit Moscow later this month to repair
the fence in the U.S.-Russian relations that was undermined by
NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia. "It's all part of maintaining good
stable relations with them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have kept up our diplomatic relations with them; I hope
that we can restore, on a more cordial basis, our military-to-
military contacts," Cohen added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
