<HEADLINE> Nepali Police Detain 7 Tamils Before President's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali police have detained
seven ethnic Tamils in Kathmandu days before the Sri Lanka
president's scheduled visit to Nepal, The Kathmandu Post reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Police suspected that the detainees are associated with Sri
Lanka's separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Elam (LTTE) and may
involve themselves in "undesirable activities," the
English-language daily said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting the Sri Lankan government
since 1983 for an independent Tamil homeland in the north and east
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka President Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga is
scheduled to start a four-day state visit to Nepal on July 5.
</P>
<P>
Police were quoted as saying that the detainees had been
changing their hotels almost on a daily basis since they entered
Nepal through India and they claimed themselves to be Indian
nationals and Pakistani nationals but the documents and passports
found from them belied their false statements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
