<HEADLINE> South Korean President Leaves for North American Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
said Friday that Pyongyang's missiles development program and
South Korea's economic reform will top the agenda at his
forthcoming meetings with U.S. President Bill Clinton and Canadian
Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
In a statement just before leaving for a six-day tour of the
United States and Canada, Kim said he needs deeper discussions
with Clinton on South Korea's national security and his "sunshine
policy" of engaging the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (
DPRK).
</P>
<P>
"I will reaffirm the pledge for continuous economic reforms
during my U.S. visit and discuss issues on international
cooperation with U.S. President Bill Clinton," said Kim, who will
stay three days in the United States.
</P>
<P>
This is Kim's third visit to the United States since he became
president in February 1998. 
