<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Waste Management Gets International Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua)-- The Philippines will benefit from the
funding from World Bank, Asian Development Bank and other
financial institutions in the process of improving its solid waste
management program.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a recent summit in the northern city of Dagupan,
Rotor Dacanay, manager for Environmental Projects of Pennoni
International Philippines, Inc., said World Bank alone has
committed 40 million dollars of the proposed 100 million dollars
for the 10-year-long program.
</P>
<P>
The summit on solid waste management was held to generate
awareness of the people on the present problem of garbage in their
communities, Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Dacanay who was an environmental specialist, the
program is divided into three phases, the first of which involved
the establishment of six sanitary landfills in the countryside
from 1999 to 2001.
</P>
<P>
Based on the estimate made by the Metro Manila Development
Authority, constructing a landfill today costs from 21 million to
26 million pesos (530,000 to 650,000 U.S. dollars) per hectare,
excluding land acquisition.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that acquisition of landfill site is difficult and
expensive, Dacanay proposed that the host community be compensated
in the form of tax incentives, cash payments and construction of
local improvement projects.
</P>
<P>
Landfill is essential component of any municipal waste
management system because large segment of municipal waste
requires disposal, he added.
</P>
<P>
Among other alternative strategies on solid waste management
mentioned by Dacanay aside from landfill disposal are source
reduction, recycling, composting, collection and transfer and
incineration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
