<HEADLINE> Foreigners Are Allowed to Buy Shares in Vietnamese Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese government has authorized
equitised companies in 11 economic sectors to sell shares to
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai approved such sales of
shares in former state-owned enterprises in a decision issued and
came into effect on Monday, according to local press Friday.
</P>
<P>
Khai's decision covers equitised companies in the following
sectors: garment; shoe; leather processing; farm produce and
seafood production and processing; household items; construction
materials; road transportation, inland waterway transportation and
container shipping; services and hotel services; engineering
production and units exporting the above items.
</P>
<P>
However, the decision says that foreign investors are not
allowed to buy shares worth more than 30 percent of a company's
total authorized capital.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam's decision aims to mobilize capital, advanced
technology and management skills from foreign companies to raise
the equitised companies' production, competitiveness and sale.
</P>
<P>
The equitisation of Vietnam's state-owned enterprises, which
started in 1993, is proceeding slowly. Up to date, only 175
state-owned enterprises were equitised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
