<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Private Power Plant to Start Trial Production in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's first 100 percent
locally-owned private power plant is to start trial production of
electricity by November this year, an English newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 70-megawatt gas-turbine power plant, which has been built
by the Rural Power Company (RPC), has already been installed in
the country's northern district of Mymensingh, The Financial
Express quoted RPC's Managing Director Maksudul karim as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plant was installed by a consortium of the MES company of
Japan and the AGT company of France under an agreement signed in
September 1997, Karim stated, adding that a similar accord was
signed with the French company for installation of two other units
with similar capacity, at the same place by August 2000.
</P>
<P>
The third plant, with same generation capacity, would be
installed at the site covering 8.4 hectares of land at a later
stage, according to the RPC managing director.
</P>
<P>
The total cost for installation of the first plant was
estimated at 62 million U.S. dollars, of which 41 million dollars
had been provided by the Asian Development Bank, while the
remaining amount came from the sponsors of the company, he
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The entire electricity produced by the plant would be purchased
by the Power Development Board (PDB), and negotiations on price
were still going on, he added.
</P>
<P>
At present, only about 15 percent of the total population in
Bangladesh has access to electricity. The present capacity of the
PDB with 52 generation units under 18 power stations is between
2,000 and 2,100 megawatts, whereas the country's total need is
about 2,300 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The government has adopted the policy of privatizing the power
sector and of encouraging private sector to take part in
development of power sector, with a view to improving the serious
situation of power shortage in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
