<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Beat Germany 3-2 to Enter World Cup Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The heavily favored United
States came from behind to beat Germany 3-2 in a quarterfinal of
the Women's World Cup here tonight.
</P>
<P>
The victory made the host team to gain a berth for the 2000
Olympics and a place of the top four.
</P>
<P>
Cheered by a yelling packed-crowd of 54,600 at the Jack Kent
Cooke Stadium and watched by U.S. President Bill Clinton and his
wife, the U.S. team rallying from a 2-1 deficit to outshoot the
European champions in the live-or-death game.
</P>
<P>
The Americans, Olympic winners with three straight victories
from Group A, looked nervous at the beginning and silenced the
crowd with a own goal by Brandi Chastain in the fifth minute.
</P>
<P>
After 11 minutes, the U.S. team levelled the score through
Tiffeny Milbrett. The Americans dominated the court and forced
five corners in the first half, but it were the Germans who surged
ahead in the 46th minute when Bettina Wigegmann blasted a close-
range shot into the left corner of the net.
</P>
<P>
Trailing 1-2, the Americans roaring back strongly in the second
half. Their efforts were paid off in the 49th minute when Chastain
seized an opportunity ball from a U.S. corner and put it into the
net.
</P>
<P>
With the score tying at 2-all, the Americans found their
composure and confidence, pressing the Germans with waves of
attacking. In the 46th minute, substitute Shannon MacMillan sent a
low and sizzling corner into the goal area where Joy Fawcett
jumped timely to hit in a brilliant header.
</P>
<P>
Referee Martha Toro Pardo of Columbia only flashed one yellow
card in the game.
</P>
<P>
In another quarterfinal tonight, Brazil beat Nigeria 4-3 in
extra time to book the last perth in the top four.  
</P>
</TEXT>
