<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Reshuffle Expected in Next Week: Thai PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
said the planned government reshuffle would be conducted no later
than next week, Channel 9, the state TV station, reported here
Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on Thursday, Chuan said the Social Action
Party (SAP) was still considered part of the coalition despite
vows made by part of its legislators to join the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Democrat Party Secretary-General Sanan Kachornprasart said on
Thursday that a meeting within the coalition will be held before
July 4 to end the government reshuffle as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The SAP was split when rebel faction's demand on ex-leader
Suvit Khunkitti quitting his science minister portfolio was
refused.
</P>
<P>
Rebel factions leaders, Party Advisor Rakkiat Sukthana and
Party Secretary-General Somsak Thepsuthin, who command nine of the
party's 20 members of parliament, have vowed to withdraw the
support for the Chuan government and join the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Suvit, by resigning as party leader, forced the party to hold
an executive committee election later Friday, of which he has
confidence to win.
</P>
<P>
So far, Deputy Industry Minister Suriya Chuengrungruangkit from
SAP had also resigned, clearing all the five ministerial posts
allocated to the party in the coalition government pending the
party's election meeting.
</P>
<P>
Other parties in the coalition are also preparing for the
upcoming government reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Banharn Silpa-archa, leader of Chart Thai Party, which holds 39
seats in the lower house, has said that his party is well prepared
for the reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, Education Minister Panja Kesornthong from
the Chart Thai Party resigned to clear the way for a reshuffle of
more cabinet posts among the party.
</P>
<P>
Both Banharn and Chart Pattana leader Korn Dabaransi had said
that they hope the SAP could stay within the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The SAP's future of whether to stay in the coalition government
or end in the opposition will be decided at Friday's executive
committee election.
</P>
<P>
However, political analysts said it is difficult for the SAP to
come to a conclusion in just one day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
