<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic Summary at 0500 GMT, July 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The UK manufacturing industry expanded for the first
time for more than a year in June as both domestic and overseas
orders increased, according to the latest research.
</P>
<P>
The return to growth comes on the back of increasing orders and
higher factory output, the research by the Chartered Institute of
Purchasing and Supply (CIPS) found. It's purchasing managers index
was 50.4 in June, up from 49.4 in May and the first reading above
50 since March last year when it was 51.1. A figure above 50
indicates expansion, below 50 contraction. (UK-Manufacturing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italy is entitled to tap into 15.5 percent of European
Union (EU) structural funds over the period 2000-2006, following
the European Commission's approval Thursday of the bloc's next
seven-year aid package for economically-depressed areas.
</P>
<P>
Italy will be able to take advantage of some 55 trillion lire (
about 30 billion U.S. dollars) in EU funding, with the lion's
share going to the underdeveloped south, and it is hoped that it
will improve its notorious reputation for making the worst use of
its structural fund allowance of any EU member. Declining
industrial areas in northern and central Italy will be allowed
some 5 trillion lire, while 7.25 trillion lire has been earmarked
for employment-boosting initiatives in these areas and 186 billion
lire for the fishing industry. (Italy-EU-Fund)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia enjoyed a surplus of 8.40 billion U.S.
dollars in its trade with foreign countries in the first five
months of this year, national newspapers Friday quoted the Central
Bureau of Statistics (BPS) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's exports in the January-May period were valued at 18.
07 billion dollars, while its imports reached 9.67 billion dollars.
But the exports dropped by 10.03 percent compared with the 20.09
billion dollars in the same period last year due to a 10.64-
percent drop in the export of non-oil/non-gas commodities to 14.88
billion dollars from 16.65 billion dollars. (Indonesia-Trade
Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's Finance Ministry issued 200 million
euros worth of bonds (about 206.8 million U.S. dollars) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five-year bonds, arranged mainly by Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, will yield 8.78 percent annually. This is the second
issuing of euro bonds by Argentina so far this year. (Argentina-
Euro Bonds) 
</P>
</TEXT>
