<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Families Spend More on Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Thrifty Chinese are exhibiting a
greater propensity to lavish money on education, especially when
it comes to educating their children.
</P>
<P>
Education expenditures for the average family in south China's
Guangdong Province have grown by some 12 percent annually for the
past three years, with per capita spending rising from 313 yuan in
1995 to 443 yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
That margin of increase for education expenditures is
substantially higher than the level for both entertainment and
travel.
</P>
<P>
Education expenditures in such cities as Guangzhou, Shenzhen
and Zhuhai rank closely behind savings deposits as the destination
for disposable income. Residents in related cities tend to retain
a certain portion of savings for housing, automobiles and travel.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of spending on education goes to educate children.
Funds mainly cover tuition and fees and extracirricular training
for special skills such as piano and art.
</P>
<P>
Continuing education for Guangdong adults has also gained
increasing popularity, with per capita spending for related
activities reaching 58 yuan in 1998, up some 50 percent on the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Private schools are playing an increasingly important role in
offering educational opportunities. Related schools have trained 2.
6 million Guandong residents since 1979.
</P>
<P>
Some 230,000 people attended private schools in 1998 in spite
of tuition costs reaching as high as several thousand yuan.
</P>
<P>
Major universities have increased fees for the most popular
specialized subject areas. For example, MBA majors attending the
South China University of Science and Engineering pay annual
tuition and fees totaling 10,000 yuan, with an additional 1,000
yuan going for textbooks.
</P>
<P>
University President Qian Ning noted that people are gaining an
increasing awareness of the important part education will play in
enabling them to compete in a knowledge-based economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
