<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Detain Meat Imports From Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka will detain meat
consignments originating from Europe following reports of dioxin
contamination detected in Belgium, said the Ministry of Livestock
Development and Estate Infrastructure on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a press release that it will detain
poultry, pork products and pet foods arriving particularly from
Belgium, the Netherlands and France.
</P>
<P>
The measure was being taken in response to reports that a fat
product from a rendering company in Europe was contaminated and
had been subsequently sold to feed manufacturers primarily in
Belgium and also other European countries, notably the Netherlands
and France, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The fats could have been mixed in compounded feeds given to
poultry and pigs and could pose a threat to human health.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly the animal quarantine staff in Colombo will detain
consignments of meat that have been already shipped or imported
into Sri Lanka from Europe, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
These consignments will be released after being cleared through
laboratory tests, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
