<HEADLINE> Indonesian Enjoys Trade Surplus in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia enjoyed a surplus of 8.40
billion U.S. dollars in its trade with foreign countries in the
first five months of this year, national newspapers Friday quoted
the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's exports in the January-May period were valued at
18.07 billion dollars, while its imports reached 9.67 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the exports dropped by 10.03 percent compared with the
20.09 billion dollars in the same period last year due to a
10.64-percent drop in the export of non-oil/non-gas commodities to
14.88 billion dollars from 16.65 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the export of oil/gas commodities also dropped by
7.07 percent to 3.19 billion dollars from 3.44 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's oil exports dropped by 15.84 percent to 284.3
billion dollars and gas exports declined by 19.97 percent to 1.35
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the export of crude oil increased to 1.55 billion dollars
from 1.41 billion dollars because of an increase in the price of
oil in the world market which rose to 16.94 dollars per barrel in
May from 15.12 dollars per barrel in April.
</P>
<P>
The import of gas/oil dropped by 16.44 percent to 1.10 billion
dollars from 1.32 billion dollars, while that of non-oil/non-gas
commodities dropped by 12.84 percent to 8.57 billion dollars from
9.84 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The import of oil dropped by 40.81 percent to 374 million
dollars and that of gas declined by 95.31 percent to 6.1 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the import of crude oil grew 41.64 percent to 163.7 million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
