<HEADLINE> Brazil's Bankruptcies More Than Double in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of Brazilian companies
that went bankrupt reached 23,733 in the five years between July
1994 and June 1999, up 168 percent from the 1989-1994 period, an
official report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most affected are companies, notably in the clothing and
electricity sectors, that failed to adapt themselves to the Plan
Real launched in 1994 and designed to reduce inflation, and to the
new foreign trade system.
</P>
<P>
However, company profitability in this period grew by an
average of 1.8 percent, thanks to the increase of foreign trade,
the report said. 
</P>
