<HEADLINE> Mayon Volcano Growing Restive in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Philippine volcanologists on
Thursday issued alert Level 2 as Mayon volcano showed persistent
tremors, elevated sulfur dioxide emission and slight swelling.
</P>
<P>
The national newspaper Malaya quoted the experts Friday as
saying that if the volcanic tremors and other physical indicators
persist, Mayon could erupt again in weeks, if not days.
</P>
<P>
The higher alert level expanded the six-kilometer permanent
danger zone under Level 1 to seven kilometers on the southeastern
side of the volcano.
</P>
<P>
"We have been monitoring weak to moderate steam emissions since
yesterday morning," said Ed Laguerta, resident volcanologist at
the Lingnon Hill observatory.
</P>
<P>
A slight increase in the sulfur dioxide emission, from 2,300
tons per day to 3,370 tons, means magma is moving up to crater,
emitting more gas along the way.
</P>
<P>
volcanic tremors are another indication magma is ascending to
the crater.
</P>
<P>
The experts said people should keep away from the danger zone
because of sudden explosions that may generate hazardous volcanic
flows.
</P>
<P>
They said residents outside the danger zone but staying within
eight kilometers from crater should be prepared to leave their
homes anytime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Promises to Fulfill Total Withdrawal From Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States will strictly
carry out the Torrijos-Carter Treaties it signed with Panama and
return every installation to the country before the year 2000, U.S.
Ambassador to Panama Simon Ferro said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ferro was speaking at a ceremony marking the closure of the
military TV network of the Southern Command (SCN), which has
transmitted its radio and television signals for Panama and the
rest of the world for 58 years.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the telecommunication network represented the
end of a period, but this was done in fulfillment of the Torrijos-
Carter Treaties, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the past five decades, the SCN provided reports and
entertainment to American soldiers housed in military bases
situated on the sides of Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
Commander of U.S. Southern Army Philip R. Kensinger said that
during its 58 years of operation, the military communication
network produced more than 3,500 hours of live radio transmission
from Panama and 240 interviews by U.S. Army, Marine and Air Force
Commanders.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the network's director, Gordon Martel,
announced that the SCN will stop producing programs from Panama as
from Thursday, but will keep on transmitting satellite programs
from the United States until December 31.
</P>
<P>
Only when the Southern Army moves to Puerto Rico, all
properties are transferred to Panama and the last soldier turns
off his light will the SCN definitely end its transmissions, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Torrijos-Carter Treaties signed in 1977, the United
States will withdraw all troops from its military bases in the
Canal zone and turn over the sovereignty and administration back
to Panama by December 31, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
