<P>
Speaking at a World Economic Forum (WEF) summit of central
European leaders in Salzburg, Austria, the Russian premier
insisted that economic assistance to the war-torn Yugoslavia for
its rehabilitation must not be conditional on the ouster of
President Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
"Russia believes that providing not only humanitarian but also
economic assistance should not be conditional on any demands or
provisions or reservations given ...sympathies or lack of such
with regard to the Milosevic regime," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Provision of such assistance ... would to my mind create more
favorable conditions for the people of Yugoslavia to make the
correct political choice during the current year," he said,
emphasizing that no problems could ever be solved by force.
</P>
<P>
He said the NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) attack
against Yugoslavia was "the biggest disaster in Europe in the
second half of the current century". And it complicated the
relations between Russia and the Western nations.
</P>
<P>
The Russian premier also said that his country actively
supports the EU-led Balkans Stability Pact for the region.
</P>
<P>
Moscow intended to take the most active part in the
establishment of mechanisms which will be established in
accordance with the pact, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Deregulate Export of Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian government Thursday
adopted amendments to the Ordinance Concerning the Export and
Import of Currency Assets to deregulate the export of currency.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendments, people can freely carry currency
equivalent up to 2,000 new redenominated leva (about 1,100 U.S.
dollars) out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Declaration to the customs is required for export of currency
between 2,000 and 20,000 new leva and a permit of the National
Bank of Bulgaria is needed for export of over 20,000 new leva.
</P>
<P>
The redenomination will take effect in Bulgaria as from July 5
with 1,000 old leva becoming equal to one new lev.
</P>
<P>
Without the amendments, people can freely carry currency
amounting to no more than 1,000 U.S. dollars aboard. A bank permit
is required for export of currency surpassing this sum.
</P>
<P>
As for the remittance overseas through bank, the amendments
rule that only an application to the bank, which should tell the
reason for the remittance, is required for the remittance of below
1,000 new leva.
</P>
<P>
Currently, a permit of the Bulgarian treasury is required for
any sum of money to be remitted overseas.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners importing big sums of money should declare them to
avoid problems when exporting them back, according to the
amendments, which will take effect 30 days after the approval by
the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
