<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Graf Wins Williams Thriller </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Steffi Graf of Germany defied the
wet weather to complete a superb three-set victory over Venus
Williams in the women's singles quarter-finals at Wimbledon tennis
championships here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The six-time champion secured her place in the last four with a
6-2, 3-6, 6-4 success in a match that was halted by the rain on
four separate occasions.
</P>
<P>
A match that was due to begin on Centre Court at 12:00 BST, was
not completed until 20:15, when the German second seed finally
wrapped up the win.
</P>
<P>
Both players were at the top of their game in a thrilling
contest that would have made a worthy final for the championships.
</P>
<P>
After the longest break of all, for two-and-a-half hours, the
match resumed in fading light with 19-year-old American Williams
ahead 2-1 on serve in the third set.
</P>
<P>
The turning point came in the fifth game when Graf, applying
pressure on every shot, broke for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
After a furious corner-to-corner rally, Graf converted with a
forehand winner.
</P>
<P>
Graf saved three break points in the next games as Williams
blew a simple forehand volley that would have levelled the match.
</P>
<P>
Williams was stretched all over the court by Graf's variety of
angles and the occasional drop-shot but the American kept fighting.
</P>
<P>
It was enthralling action and just what the fans who had waited
nearly eight hours on court deserved.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the games went with serve, with Graf converting on
her first match point. When sixth seed Williams hit a forehand
wide, Graf hopped up and down on the baseline, punching the air
and screaming with delight.
</P>
<P>
Graf paid tribute to her opponent and predicted it would not be
long before she became the dominant player on the WTA Tour.
</P>
<P>
"She is very tough, I knew that beforehand and that's partly
why I am so happy because she is a strong player," said the 31-
year-old Graf.
</P>
<P>
"She has a big serve, moves incredibly well and she got some
balls back that I thought were over.
</P>
<P>
"Two years ago you could see what potential she has and I've
said it before and I'll say it again, she will be world number one.
</P>
<P>
"She has the game and the physique. She has a lot of talent.
She can do a lot of things out there. It rarely happens that you
have to play tennis like that in a quarter-final.
</P>
<P>
"We played unbelievable tennis. To play so well and be in the
semis is very exciting, " she added.
</P>
<P>
Williams meanwhile refused to blame the rain delays for her
defeat. "You have to be prepared to compete any time a match is
called," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I really wasn't thinking about the conditions. I had no issue
with it. It doesn't matter what happens, you have to be ready to
play tennis and can't let outside influences distract you.
</P>
<P>
"I think I was able to come back and still compete after each
delay and I don't think it affected me too much.
</P>
<P>
"Steffi has been through more rain delays than I've ever
dreamed of so everything is an experience," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Champion Novotna Crashes Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Jana Novotna's reign as Wimbledon
champion came to an abrupt end, as Lindsay Davenport romped to a
straight sets victory in the women's singles quarter-finals on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Third seed Davenport reached her first ever semi-final at the
All England Club, with a 6-3, 6-4 triumph as rain disrupted play
for the third day of the championships.
</P>
<P>
Czech veteran Novotna failed to find the form that secured her
an emotional first Grand Slam title last year as she was
dispatched with ease by her American opponent.
</P>
<P>
Davenport dominated the error-prone fifth seed in a lackluster
match to extend her career record against Novotna to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
After the start of the match was delayed an hour by rain,
Davenport set the tone by breaking Novotna to love in the first
game. She then broke twice more to take the opening set in 32
minutes.
</P>
<P>
The second set was delayed at 4-3 for an hour by rain - but
when play resumed 23-year-old Davenport put Novotna out of her
misery.
</P>
<P>
Novotna, who won last year after two defeats in the final, was
playing in her 14th Wimbledon. At age 30, she may not have many
more chances to win again.
</P>
<P>
Both players denied that Novotna's ankle injury, which she
suffered playing doubles in the French Open, had been a
significant factor in her defeat.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure it affected her preparation coming to Wimbledon, "
Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
"But she's now been playing for at least 12 days on grass, so I
thought she actually came up with some good shots. I thought she
played well."
</P>
<P>
And Novotna added: "My ankle was just fine, I was moving fine.
</P>
<P>
"It seemed to get better and better, here. She played once
again with her serve and power groundstrokes. They were too good,"
she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
