<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Still Plagued by Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Tennis fans have suffered another
frustrating time at Wimbledon, as persistent rain continued to
play havoc on the third day of the second week.
</P>
<P>
Players were kept off court for most of the day on Wednesday
when only two of the scheduled quarter-finals were completed.
</P>
<P>
After third seed Lindsay Davenport beat defending champion Jana
Novotna in the women's singles, Wimbledon legend Steffi Graf put
out the American Venus Williams in three thrilling sets in a later
time.
</P>
<P>
Home hero Tim Henman was able to start his much-anticipated
last eight clash with Cedric Pioline.
</P>
<P>
But after the Briton had won the first game and was well placed
at deuce on the Frenchman's serve, the rain returned and the
players were unable to resume their match.
</P>
<P>
It was the third day this week where the rain has wiped out
most of the meaningful action.
</P>
<P>
Tournament organisers now face a major headache to try to
reschedule the remaining matches.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon chief executive Christopher Gorringe revealed that
the women's final may be moved from Saturday to Sunday
</P>
<P>
"The most realistic plan is that we would play the semi-finals
on Saturday and both finals on Sunday," he told BBC TV.
</P>
<P>
"We haven't decided which order the men's and women's finals
would be, we'll have to wait and see."
</P>
<P>
Gorringe added that the All England Club still hopes to avoid
carrying the tournament over into a third week.
</P>
<P>
"We're still planning to finish on Sunday," he confirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
