<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man United Sacrifices 'in Vain' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The unprecedented move to let
Manchester United miss next season's FA Cup is unlikely to improve
England's chances of hosting the 2006 World Cup, according to
football's governing body FIFA on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Football Association has allowed holders United to sit out
the FA Cup so they can take part in the inaugural World Team
Championship in Brazil next January.
</P>
<P>
The FA believes that by taking part in the new tournament,
which is the brainchild of FIFA president Sepp Blatter, United
will aid England's campaign to win the race for 2006.
</P>
<P>
United accepted the argument and on Wednesday they reluctantly
withdrew from the FA Cup -- against the wishes of many of their
supporters, who have been vocal in their condemnation of the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
However FIFA's head of communications Keith Cooper has warned
that United's sacrifice could be unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the theory that United have improved the 2006 bid
and insisted the World Team Championship is a separate issue from
who hosts the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
"I think the two things are completely separate," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The position on who will host the World Cup in 2006 will be
taken by the 24 members of the executive committee in March next
year and the criteria that they choose to apply is entirely their
business."
</P>
<P>
Cooper's comments will add further fuel to the controversy
raging over United's withdrawal from the oldest and most famous
knockout competition in the world.
</P>
<P>
But one of the leading figures within international football
took the opposing view and feels England's hopes have been boosted
by the United situation.
</P>
<P>
Trinidad &AMP; Tobago's Jack Warner, a FIFA vice president and
president of the north and central American federation, CONCACAF,
welcomed the move.
</P>
<P>
Warner, one of 24 FIFA officials who will vote on who hosts the
2006 World Cup, said: "This can only augur well for England's bid
to host World Cup 2006.
</P>
<P>
"If England want to be taken seriously by the world of football
it's only right they take the world of football seriously
themselves.
</P>
<P>
"I am therefore very pleased to hear that Manchester United
will be taking part. It speaks volumes for the efforts of the club
and country," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990702.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Cuts Lending Rates for Second Half of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank announced
here Friday that it has reduced its lending rates on the U.S.
dollar loan facility from 6.38 percent to 6.24 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
"The rate on multi-currency loans has also been decreased from
5.84 percent to 5.65 percent per annum," the ADB said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said that the new lending rates apply
from July 1 to December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates on the ADB's multi-currency and U.S. dollar
loans are adjusted on January 1 and July 1 each year.
</P>
<P>
For each facility, the lending rate is determined by adding a
spread (currently 0.4 percent per annum) to the preceding six
months' average cost of the respective pools of the bank's
outstanding borrowings established to fund such loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
