<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Statement to Be Issued Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Ireland will on Friday
make a statement on the next stage of the stalled Northern Irish
peace accord, a British official said as negotiations continued
late on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The two governments will make a joint statement on the way
forward tomorrow," the Reuters news agency quoted the spokesman
for British Prime Minister Tony Blair as saying.
</P>
<P>
The governments would receive a report on Friday from the
Northern Ireland's disarmament commission on prospects for
guerrilla disarmament. The government statement would be based on
its content and an assessment of submissions made by the parties
involved in the talks, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Intensive talks have been under way in Belfast for four days in
an attempt to rescue the year-old Good Friday agreement, which has
been paralyzed by a dispute between pro-British Unionists and
Irish Republicans about guerrilla disaramament and the formation
of a power-sharing provincial government. 
</P>
