<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Peace Talks Given One More Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The talks to resolve the Northern
Ireland peace process are to continue Friday after a fourth day of
negotiations failed to find a solution to the impasse over weapons
decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
The UK and Irish governments will make a statement Friday on
the way forward in the peace process. The report by General John
de Chastelain on the readiness of paramilitary groups to disarm is
also to be presented to political parties.
</P>
<P>
The marathon talks at the Stormont Castle Buildings in Belfast
involving the Ulster Unionists continued into the night Thursday.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern spent Thursday in discussions but there has yet to be
any sign of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
A document containing the various proposals put by the
different sides in the talks has now been distributed to all
parties involved in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday evening, Blair met Ulster Unionist assembly members
to hear their views on decommissioning. The party's chief
negotiator, Sir Reg Empey, said the key purpose of the meeting was
to allow the assembly members to tell the prime minister how
important decommissioning was to them.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has appealed to both sides to
resolve their differences, saying it would be "very hard" for the
world to understand if the talks broke down without a deal,
according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Blair's official spokesman has said the prime minister believes
there could be a handover of IRA (Irish Republican Army) weapons,
but he refused to confirm whether Sinn Fein, the IRA's political
wing, had produced any concrete proposals.
</P>
<P>
The main sticking point Thursday was the disagreement between
the two sides over whether Sinn Fein had made any concrete
proposals regarding decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's First Minister David Trimble insisted that
no commitment had been given by Sinn Fein to start decommissioning
because he had seen nothing in writing.
</P>
<P>
Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, immediately dubbed Trimble
's comments as "fabrication."
</P>
<P>
The political leaders were asked to write down their positions
Thursday evening. The prime minister's spokesman said there were
a series of papers on the table covering "what is do-able."
</P>
<P>
The impasse stems from the insistence of the Ulster Unionists
that they will not sit with Sinn Fein in Northern Ireland's
government without a start to arms decommissioning by the IRA.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein maintains it cannot guarantee this and points out it
is not in the Good Friday Agreement, which demands disarmament by
all groups by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
Adams' party suggested a timetable for decommissioning before
May 2000, on condition that the Unionists accept them into an
executive. But Trimble insists weapons must be handed over at the
same time legislative powers are transferred from London to
Belfast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
