<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Get 15.5 Percent of EU Structural Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy is entitled to tap into 15.5
percent of European Union (EU) structural funds over the period
2000-2006, following the European Commission's approval Thursday
of the bloc's next seven-year aid package for
economically-depressed areas.
</P>
<P>
Italy will be able to take advantage of some 55 trillion lire
(about 30 billion U.S. dollars) in EU funding, with the lion's
share going to the underdeveloped south (43 trillion lire), and it
is hoped that it will improve its notorious reputation for making
the worst use of its structural fund allowance of any EU member.
</P>
<P>
Declining industrial areas in northern and central Italy will
be allowed some 5 trillion lire, while 7.25 trillion lire has been
earmarked for employment-boosting initiatives in these areas and
186 billion lire for the fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
On an annual basis, Italy will be entitled to almost 8 trillion
lire per year, against the 6.6 trillion a year set down in the
previous seven-year funding package.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission approved plans to set aside a total of
412 trillion lire in structural funds for the bloc's economic
trouble spots over the 2000-2006 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
