<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Urges to Establish Institutions in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo must begin establishing all the
institutions-from courts to classrooms-necessary to turn the
standing military order into a civil society, Italian Defense
Minister Carlo Scognamiglio said Thursday during hearings of the
defense committee of the Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The time has come for Kosovo to move as soon as possible from
the military to civil phase," said Scognamiglio, adding that "It
is an essential transformation."
</P>
<P>
He said Kosovo needs governors, judges, doctors and teachers
because "the military alone cannot restore the Balkan region to a
normal life."
</P>
<P>
According to United Nations resolution 1244, civil
administrations must be established to govern while NATO troops
work to guarantee the peace.
</P>
<P>
Scognamiglio, who recently returned from a tour of Kosovo, also
called for the prompt naming of a chief UN commissioner to oversee
the resettlement and reconstruction of the territory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
